animal.breeds_label: American Bulldog & Pit Bull Terrier Mix
animal.description:
Do you love to walk and hike and run?  Do you have a dog that loves to play?  If you answered YES to these questions, then Austin Powers is the dog for you! This boy is a spitfire full of energy and one happy, playful puppy!

Austin Powers (AP for short) is a gorgeous, affectionate American Bulldog mix who is one year old, weighs 40 lbs, and is looking for his loving, forever family!  He is eager to please and knows basic commands. He has had professional training and is very food motivated.  He is an extremely athletic and dog friendly dog! He loves people so much that he "talks" to them!  A home with children over 15 or an adult only home would be best since he is still a puppy and needs someone who will continue to train him. His playful energy & exuberance could easily knock over a young child.  Austin is looking for a home with a fenced yard & someone who is very active (maybe a jogger) since he has enough energy to think that a 3 mile jog is the warmup!  He would also do very will attending doggy day care once or twice a week, especially if his people work outside the home.  He loves to make friends with other dogs and would be great with a family that already has a dog that loves to play!  Austin loves his crate and is crate trained, housebroken, neutered, fully vaccinated & microchipped. 

For more information about AP, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt sweet Austin, please submit an application for him at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Paisley promises to help keep you moving in the New Year and meet all your fitness goals! Paisley is looking for an active owner who will take her for daily walks and help her stay mentally and physically challenged. Paisley is a goofy, smart dog who grew up on the streets in Houston, Texas but came here to Iowa to find her forever family. She just got her dog DNA back for her Christmas gift and found out that while we already knew she is 100% a great dog, she is made up of 36% American Staffordshire Terrier, 25% American Bulldog, 13% Rottweiler, 12% Boxer, 9% German Shepherd, and 5% Labrador Retriever. Paisley loves everything and everyone and has a zest for play and life in general. Because she's extremely playful and smart she would do best with other pets and humans with similar play styles as she might be overwhelming to really young children or elderly pets. She gets along well with the kids, dogs, and cat in her current foster home. If a future owner has a fence, Paisley needs it to be a tall privacy fence and very secure as Paisley can jump really high, climb chain link, and open latches. Because of her love of fence climbing, Paisley would also be happy to have an owner without a fence who is 100% committed to leashed potty breaks and daily walks or runs.

Paisley Blue's adoption fee is $250 and includes her spay, microchip, current vaccinations and preventatives PLUS a free obedience course at Cedar Run Pet Boarding & Daycare in Hiawatha. Last Hope requires that all animals be kept as indoor pets only, be altered and current on vaccinations and preventatives. Our adoption process includes reference and background checks, a vet check and a home visit. Please apply at Adopthope.org for consideration.

animal.description:
Momo is a very special girl who is just the right size, looking for just the right home!  We are networking with Midcoast Humane hoping to help Momo find that.  Momo was rescued from a living situation that was very challenging.  This sweetheart is going to need an understanding, patient, and dog- experienced owner who will continue to guide her as she fully blossoms to be the best girl she can be!   She is very smart, is an eager learner, and has already mastered several cues.  She loves to play, play, play, and she adores her toys!  Due to her high energy and playful spirit, she will need a home that has solid wood or chain link fence.  She walks loosely on a leash but will pull if she wants to follow her nose. This terrific girl is looking for a quiet, yet active adult-only home, without a lot of traffic in and out.  She is on daily medication that she happily gobbles down in her “meatball” of wet dog food.  She is looking for a lifetime commitment and the shelter will require at least two meetings with her new family to ensure this is the best fit for everyone.  No children, dogs, cats, or any other pets in the home, please!

If you’re interested in adoption, please fill out our online adoption survey at http://olddogsnewdigs.com/form-adoption.html.

Please share so that we can help find Momo her new family!

animal.description:
Pepper is a Lab/Pit mix, born July 2016. She came into rescue with her puppies, and they have all been adopted. She is doing amazing now without her puppies and is such a sweet, sweet girl. She does well with other dogs her size, but has not been around larger or smaller dogs. She needs a home without cats She does well with children, but she is too big and excitable for smaller kids. Her tail is a whip! Her heartworm treatment is done, and she has taken it like a champ. Some of Pepper's hobbies include looking out the window for hours, snuggling, helping herself to her bag of dog food, and hogging the bed or couch. Pepper is very athletic and can jump over a 4-foot fence with ease. Her new home must have a 6-foot fence.

The suggested adoption donation for Pepper is $350. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
Finley is 3 years old and about 45 pounds. She is a mixed breed. 
Finley came to us a very fearful puppy.  We have done a ton of work with her,  but she is afraid of almost everything.  She is jumpy at loud noises, like if you drop something.  
She is ok with us, but even after years of trying, she is still very afraid of strangers.  
Finley is a big barker.  She barks at the neighbors, she barks anytime she is afraid of something. 
The time she is most at ease is when she is playing with the other dogs. 
I know it is a stretch that she will find the right home, but maybe one is out there. 
Her home will need :
A fenced in yard, as she is a runner. If she ever gets out, I am not sure you would ever catch her. Also, she likes to play fetch, and needs a yard for that.
At least one other dog in her home 
A quiet, rural setting
A quiet home with no small children
And a super patient,  loving person that understands it will take a LOT to win her over.
She will need to be adopted locally as you will have to come several times to spend time with her before she goes to her new home. She will run and hide when anyone comes to visit.   She will not just decide she is not afraid of you. She will be a lot work, but she is a sweet girl. 
She can't be boarded if you go on vacation,  so she will need a dogsitter that will take the time to get to know her.

These are non negotiable,  as we want a successful adoption for her so that she won't be returned.  That would awful for her.

Finley is spayed and up to date on vaccinations.  Her adoption fee is $350.00
If you think you might be willing to give her a permanent,  loving home,  the first step is a completed application.  You can find them here
www.newdigsfordogsrescue.org

animal.description:
This is Thor. He's a large (100 pounds +) Yellow Labrador, just over two years old, and recently became a Lucky Paws Rescue dog. When Thor was a puppy, it was suggested that he had cateracts in his eyes. No further diagnostics or treatment was done, which led to glaucoma, and Thor is now blind. He will need to have both eyes removed, as they can be very painful (which is now being managed).

We have Thor in a wonderful, loving foster home with people who adopted a blind dog from Lucky Paws Rescue a few years ago. Our plan was to have Thor stay in this foster home until his surgery and through recovery.

After discussing with the foster, the best scenerio would be if we could find Thor his forever home now, and then move forward with the surgery after he acclimates. Lucky Paws Rescue will be taking care of the surgery costs.

In his previous home, where Thor had lived all his life, he was friendly with other dogs, cats, and people--but that was the only home he'd known, where he felt secure, and the home where he'd gone blind over time. Moving from his home to an unfamiliar place with new people, new dogs, and a new floorplan proved to be scary for Thor, and of course, being blind only intensifies everything.

The foster home has two other dogs. Being blind, he needed security in his new territory, so he quickly attached himself to his foster mom. He isn't fond of the other dogs, and even though they are friendly, Thor does not want them near him. It would be ideal to find a home without any other dogs.

He's a very sweet boy. We're looking for a loving, patient home for him that could accomodate his needs. Thor is very young, can adapt, and have a long and happy life!

animal.description:
Meet Frieda!! She is an approximately 1-year-old medium to high energy Shepherd mix. She became a misfit due to demodectic mange but she is all healed up now! She is heart worm negative, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, spayed, and micro-chipped. 

Frieda walks on a leash pretty well and does well in the car, too. She hasn't quite figured out how to sit / lay so she can easily keep her balance but she doesn't get sick and she behaves well. She is just not extremely sturdy. She has not learned any tricks while with her foster family, but she would likely learn fast with the right owner. 

She is great with other dogs and good with older children. She could be okay with younger children but would need to be monitored in case she were to **accidentally** knock them down. She REALLY wants to play with her feline foster siblings, to the point that she will chase them up their cat tree if she isn't closely monitored. Her foster family has a lot of cats around and we have no concerns that she would ever intentionally hurt them but we do worry that her trying to be their friend could result in someone being injured. We would like to see her go to a home with no cats or other small pets she would have ready access to. 

Frieda is a little slow to warm up in a new environment. We suspect she came from a not-so-great background, though we will never really "know." Once she warms up to her humans, she is the sweetest, goofiest girl! She is always climbing in "her" chair and sticking her tongue out when she knows it is time to go to bed. She loves to run and play with other dogs and would more than likely be great for someone who likes to hike or jog regularly (with some training... her leash skills aren't *that* good). She prefers women, so would do best in a home with a single woman or a couple, not a home where she would only be exposed to a man / men 24/7

You can apply to meet / adopt her at www.muttmisfits.com/adoption-application

animal.description:
Here's Newman!  Newman is an 8 year old Labrador Retriever Mix.  While we don't know much about his past, we can only assume that this sweet boy was left to his own devices way too often, which is why he gets nervous when left alone.  Newman is very sweet and easily attaches to "his" human, but he doesn't like to share his people, so he must be the only pet in his adoptive home.  Newman pulls on a leash, and at 75 pounds, can be a bit much to take for a long stroll, so he will require a fenced in yard so that he can run around and tire himself out!  Newman loves to sit on the couch and watch television with his people - he's the perfect quarantine buddy!  If he sounds like a fit for you - apply today!  His adoption fee is $150!

To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

Are you interested in giving this sweet Pit mix a second chance at life? Read what his current foster has to say about him:
Hi all! I am currently fostering this angel of a pup, Hannibal & he still needs a forever home!! 
He’s the kindest, most lovable pup I’ve ever spent time with & will cuddle all day long. He loves his bone covered in peanut butter & never gets bored of his new toy!!
He did have trauma as a puppy that makes it hard to use his jaw. He’s taking medication for it & will need occasional vet visits - but so far he’s been nothing but a blessing to me!”
Hannibal had some kind of traumatic injury to his head at some point. He is blind in one eye, in addition to not being able to open his jaw. We are currently working closely with a veterinarian to decide if Hannibal being unable to open his jaw is due to scar tissue or an autoimmune disease. He is doing well though and with your help we can give this beautiful guy a second chance. Please email awfpadoptions@gmail.com if interested in adopting!
***
Please read through our adoption policies and requirements at www.awfpva.org/adoptions or on our Petfinder homepage prior to requesting an application. 

All of our animals are in foster homes. We will schedule meet and greets after approving your adoption application to ensure our fosters are only meeting with serious applicants. Please allow 1-2 weeks for approval as AWFP is run by volunteers who are full-time veterinary students.

animal.description:
Hello there! My name is Oreo, and I am a 9 year old gal, 22 lbs, with the spunk and energy of a much younger pup! I have visited the Veterinarian where I have received some treatments, and have been very well cared for! I do have Cushings so I need a family who will ensure I continue with my medication. I am beautifully house-trained, and I loooooove people, in fact I am known as my foster mom's, shadow and I am an excellent companion. I do require a home with no other pets, secure fenced yard and I am not compatible with a doggie door. I am not destructive within the home, so I am ok to roam inside while you are away. I do love going to the office with my foster mom, and I am happy to catch a nap curled up under her desk while she is busy, but I am ready to run and play at a moment's notice! My favorite things to do daily are play ball, chew on my Himalayan Dog Chew, explore in the fenced yard and yes....I love treats! I am a joyful, loving gal looking for my forever home! I am on medications due to my Cushings that cost $70 a month with and blood tests approximately every 6 months that cost $350. My adoption fee is $75 but if you are a senior human over the age of 65 years, my adoption fee is waived! MUST BE AN ONLY DOG AND NO YOUNG CHILDREN.If you are interested in any of our Boston Terriers or would like to be eligible to adopt a Boston Terrier through our rescue in the future, please fill out an application. It can be found at www.texasbostons.com. Click on the Rescue tab and then on the Adopt Now! tab. Here you will find our adoption requirements along with a link for an online adoption application. This will allow you to get on our list of approved homes so you can immediately adopt a Boston Terrier when it becomes available through Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas.

We are always looking for good foster homes. These homes allow us to rescue more Boston Terriers in need because we have a place for them to go until they are adopted. Please consider becoming a foster home for Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas. You can fill out a foster application at www.texasbostons.com. Click on the Rescue tab and then on the Foster Program tab. Here you will find our requirements for becoming a foster parent along with a link for an online foster application. This will allow you to possibly become a foster home for one of our little Boston Terriers in need. Thank you for considering the possibility of fostering for Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas!

Any and all Donations are always needed and welcome. Because BTRNT is a 501(c) 3, all donations are tax deductible. If you wish to donate to Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas, please go to www.texasbostons.com and click on the red "Donate Now" tab at the top left of the page. If you wish to donate dog food or any other item, please mail to:

Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas

Plano, TX 75086

If you have any questions regarding Boston Terrier Rescue of North Texas please call 844-428-7776 and leave a message. Your call will be returned as soon as possible.

Thank you for your continued support in our rescue efforts! Help us Rescue The Bostons!

animal.description:
Ludo is a lover boy! He is very mild mannered and perfectly content to be asleep on his bed for most of the day as long as he has a soft bed and a cozy blanket.  If there are other dogs around his yard (beyond the fence), he will bark/challenge them with his barking like any other dog.  He loves to be held, to sleep on a lap, or in the bed with you. Due to his disabilities, he is pretty reserved and hesitant to be mobile and inquisitive.  Ludo does not mind other dogs or cats.  He will call/cry out when he is lost (in the yard) or scared.

When Ludo wakes up from sleeping, he needs to use the bathroom right away. If left for more than 4 (best case) - 6 (absolute max) hours, he will have an accident. Because Ludo is hesitant and cannot get outside quickly by himself, he needs to be carried outside to do his business.  If he is not taken outside, he will go wherever he is (on the carpet, floor, blankets, etc).  Despite being exposed to potty pads, Ludo has never used one.

Because Ludo does not see, he relies highly on his sense of smell and sound to navigate his environment. He does best in a quiet, low key environment, and an environment that is free of clutter (i.e., no small toys or items that could cause him to trip and fall). Ludo should not be in a house with stairs or a house with a pool.  A house with young children may be stressful to him.

Ludo is entirely dependent on his humans to have his needs met.  He gets excited about meal time and snacks.  He WILL steal food from others (cats or dogs) if he has the opportunity.  Ludo gets excited and barks at a knock on the door if the other dogs are also barking.  Ludo needs a home that will be patient with him and understand his disabilities.  He needs a home that has several soft beds for him to rest.
animal.name: Ludo-Houston area

animal.special_needs_notes:
Ludo is completely blind due to a protein buildup in his eyes.  He is also missing his left front leg due to an accident he suffered several years ago. Ludo also has a very sensitive gastrointestinal tract and eats a specific diet. Small changes to his diet can cause major GI upset.  He has a tendency towards an infection around his penis.  He should be frequently monitored for discharge, but will often display signs of infection by whimpering or licking the area.

Occasional accidents - Ludo does well with his potty habits most of the time if they are managed by a human. He sleeps most of the day, so whenever he gets up, it is a sign that he needs to go out. His maximum time without a potty break is about 4 hours. He does have multiple bowel movements throughout the day and these are usually done at the same time he goes out.  Ludo does routinely wake up in the night and need to go to the bathroom.  He does not indicate the need to go out, but if taken outside as soon as he wakes, he will not have an accident.

animal.description:
Little Ann is a 1 yr old spaniel/terrier mix. She weighs about 35 lbs. We estimate she will be 35-45 lbs  at most. 
She is very timid at 1st, and it takes her a while to warm up to new dogs and people. She is sweet, smart, and has a great disposition. She is completely potty trained, knows how to use a doggie door, knows come, no, uhuh, outside, and go potty commands. She is loves to chew on benebones, nylabones, bully sticks, and toys.

She was found dumped out in the country, with her brother Big Dan. We do not know how long they were on their own. I am sure they were ran off by numerous people, maybe attacked by coyotes and possibly other dogs before they found a good Samaritan who took them in and got them to our rescue.

She really loves belly rubs, wading in the kiddie pool, playing with toys, her brother, and our adult female dogs. She is crazy about pop corn, and bacon, and likes treats of all kinds. 

She will need basic training, confidence building, leash training, and continued socialization. She does not like to be crated, but does fine in her pen or a gated room.

She will do best in a home with a gentle, secure, but playful canine sibling(s) or as the only dog. A quieter home, with older or no kids, a nice securely fenced yard, and someone who is home most of the time, would be ideal.

Her family would need to be able and willing to allow her the time, patience, love, socialization, and confidence/positive reinforcement training she will need to become the great companion she is meant to be.

ALL children should be at least AGE 5 to be approved for adoption!

Please apply directly at WWW.BIGDOGRESCUEPROJECT.ORG/Adopt.

Our adoption fee of $450 includes  age appropriate vaccinations, microchipping and transport expenses.

Application will be accepted and an adopter chosen based on the needs of the dog.  We will contact you if you are chosen to adopt.

animal.description:
Hi there!

My name is Sebastian! I am 7 years old and I weigh 70 pounds!
I was part of a group of dogs that a rescue started helping in a bad part of town. Rescues had come in and picked all the youngsters and left me and my ol' lady friend all by our selves on the street. Finally after alot of networking a rescue heard we were still there and came to get us. I hopped right in her car but my friend she had to get fancy and corner in someones yard! I was so friendly I was trying to help her get my buddy the whole time! Didn't she know good people when she saw one???

I had called shotgun in the car and was immediately her best bud. I kept popping her hand off the shift to stick my head under it so she could pet me better. I'm very considerate that way and still do that whenever I'm sitting next to someone and I think they've forgotten how to pet me. They got me neutered, up to date on shots, current on heartworm/flea prevention and microchipped. Unfortunately after a long time of being on the street with no one to take care of me I was heartworm positive but I have already been through treatment and am on the mend!

I really love all people. Little ones, Big ones, tall ones and short ones it doesn't make any difference to me! I would love a home with just about anyone who would show me affection whether they've got kids or grandkids running around. I'm a little bit older boy so I don't need quite as much action as some of those young bucks out there but I still like to go for a walk down the road with my foster mom and I get super excited when I see people! I would probably do best in a home as an only dog or maybe just with a submissive female. Male dogs rile me up to much and after being on the street for so long I don't know what to expect from them! But my foster mom is still working with me all the time to make me the best boy I can be!

I am still located in Houston, Texas but am super excited to find my forever home and get transported to your area! Will you be my family? For more info on me please email Stephanie at nicole.whar94@yahoo.com.

animal.description: It will only take 20 seconds of action to understand why our very own Humane Society canine was awarded the name of the greatest soccer star to have graced this planet. When he arrived for his photo session, Pele’ hopped into the doggie pool for a 5 second refresher and then dashed to the other end of the bark park, and spent the next 15 minutes in an amazing non-stop display of agile athletic prowess that left the spectators breathless. His most prized possession is the oversized blue “soccer” ball that he brings alive with his non-stop, jaw-dropping moves that any two-legged competitor would be proud to emulate. Pele’ is the maestro of the Step Over, the Cruyff, the Cut, the Body Feint and the Scoop Turn.  Out of all the moves, his favorite is the Header, of which he is a true master.  Pele’ does an instant sit on request and takes treats with respect and gentleness. He pulls with exuberance on leash but has a caring HS volunteer working with him to moderate his energetic walk. Pele’s favorite dream is to be picked as a mascot for the LA GALAXY where he can perform his magic in front of 40,000 fans (all wearing masks, of course).  Pele’ has a high intelligence IQ that will require a human of similar presence to appreciate and fulfill the promise of sharing life with an astoundingly gifted canine.

animal.description:
Born May 5, 2019, Enzo is a male American Stafford Terrier mix seeking a forever home. Here is a little bit about him: Enzo is a medium to large pup that came into the rescue following a car accident that left him with an amputation and a broken pelvis. He recently turned one year old and is very sweet, affectionate and playful. Enzo is crate trained, potty trained, knows sit, down, kennel, and "out" (of the kitchen during meal prep, eating). He plays very well with his canine foster sister and 2 foster cats. He loves chew toys, antlers and car rides. We are working on walking nicely on leash. He corrects easily, so in no time, he should be heeling. Enzo requires a 6 foot fenced yard and would love to live with an active person or family. He has done great around young children, but he doesn't know his own strength and might accidentally knock a small one over. Enzo's best fit forever home will be with adults or adults and children over 8. He is vetted, microchipped and his pelvis has fully healed. He will make a wonderful companion for some lucky person or family! Applications: www.mikeyschance.com

All large and/or active dogs will require a full fenced (6ft) secure yard. 
No children under 5. 

Like all Mikey's Chance dogs, this dog will come to you from a foster home that has provided loving one-on-one attention, socialization and some basic training, as well as quality food and exercise. 

Applications can be found at www.mikeyschance.com and completed on a computer, tablet, and/or phone. Please note that adopters are not chosen on a first come, first served basis, but full consideration is given to the best fit for the dog AND the adopter. Applications can take up to 3 weeks to process. Application submission DO NOT guarantee approval for adoption.

animal.description:
HANDSOME DEAK (Deacon) is an energetic boy (100% chocolate lab), neutered, current on all vaccines, house trained, crate trained, approx 76lb, and just turned 7yr in January.  Don't let his age fool you because his energy level will surprise YOU !  He would be a great jogging partner if that is something you like to do routinely; he is still learning to walk at "normal" pace.  He is a bit of a speed walker... so anyone that roller blades or jogs or walks at a brisk pace can keep up with him.  He needs a large fenced yard, playtime and exercise routinely because.....we all know "A TIRED dog is a GOOD dog"   Deak enjoys tug of war with his rope toy or a kong ball, and his personal (kiddie) pool is much loved (during the summer); if there's a creek or rain puddle he will find it and partake !  Need a kiddie pool for Deak? It comes with his adoption :-)  Deak thrives on playing, exercise, eating and human companionship. His daily routine is time outside watching birds, chasing squirrels or rabbits (he has a strong prey drive so "nose work" is something you will see often from him), playtime throughout the day, nap time, sometimes a car ride , AND just hanging with his human companions wherever they are inside or outside.  He will greet his humans with toys or kisses, and he tries to be a LAP dog, so be prepared for this boy's intense level of affection   Adults are the BEST FIT for this boy with no other pets in the home. Deacon is very smart and has done very well with his training; he knows basic commands necessary to help manage his behavior, and would do best with someone dedicated to providing leadership, on-going training, exercise, playtime, and companionship. 
His ADOPTION APPLICATION is on the ADOPTME page at Dream4pets.org	
We usually adopt within a 120 mile radius of Miami County (Troy, Piqua, TippCity)   His adoption application is on the ADOPTME page at Dream4pets.org       If you have questions,Email PetsRRpassion@gmail.com

animal.description:
Levi was among a number of dogs that a neighboring area's animal control forcibly removed from their former home. We're not sure why the AC removed Levi and the other dogs but are aware that, despite a court order prohibiting them from doing so, the former owners attempted to re-gain custody of the dogs through some sneaky and underhanded methods. Each time the former owners were caught and prohibited from obtaining any of the dogs. SoCo Rescue was asked to find Levi and his buddy (see Bones' profile) new homes. Both Levi and Bones were placed in a safe foster home once we removed them from the AC facility.

While Levi's appearance and size may concern some people, in truth he's just a big mush! He's impressed his foster parents with his super-friendly personality towards people and other dogs alike and has proven to be very smart and a quick learner. While at his foster home, Levi has interacted very well with the children at the house. He also seems to be more attached to women than he does men.

Levi has now been fully vetted and recently tested negative for heartworms. He's up to date on all of his yearly vaccinations and monthly preventatives as well. He may need additional house training

If you're looking for a large dog companion that's friendly and very personable, then submit an application for Levi at socorescue.com

animal.description:
I was surrendered to the city shelter with my mother by our first owner.  I don’t know why but I knew I had to protect my mom in that scary place.  Luckily, we were saved by two volunteers who ignored my behavior understanding the reason.   A foster mom stepped up to take us both in.  My mom got adopted quickly and I do miss her but I know my foster mom found a great family for her.    I am a bit more of a challenge but my foster mom says I have improved so much.   I like to think my foster mom is not in a rush and wants to find me the perfect home.  

I am fully vetted, neutered, micro-chipped and up to date on my vaccinations.  I have to admit, I am not thrilled going to the vet so not the best patient.  I am always happy to leave!!  It is good I am a healthy pup of about three years of age.  I am a terrier of some sort, perhaps Rat or Jack Russell with some Chihuahua?  I have the cutest bobbed tail.  I weigh in at 16 pounds.  I love my food so need my weight watched.  

I am good in the car but will bark at people and dogs that walk by.  My foster mom discourages that.  I love my walks, sitting on my foster mom’s lap and being with other dogs.  I do not really play but as you can see from the pictures, we enjoy sleeping on the bed together.   I do have lots of energy and sometimes get the zoomies which includes jumping on my foster mom’s lap, then pushing myself off to circle the yard some more.   But I also calm down and retreat to my crate.

I am slow to warm up to people so it’s best to let me make the first move.    But once I like someone, we are the best of friends.  I have not been around children they do make me a bit nervous when out walking.  I would do best in an all adult home especially a single person.    Please email rhondabarron@earthlink.net for an app or go to our website www.freedomstreetrescue.org to complete an app

animal.description:
Beca is a 24 months old, female, fully vetted, current on shots, spayed Schnauzer Mix who came to us from Puerto Rico. She is ready to provide tons of love. Becca requires an experienced adopter as she is initially very shy. She relates well with other dogs and enjoys running in the yard. She is an inside/outside dog once she feels confident with the humans around her. 

Our adoption process involves 3 steps. First, we evaluate you on paper via the adoption application https://www.123formbuilder.com/form-5081187/ or the one that is available on this site. If you meet our requirements we schedule a home visit, we travel up to 1.5 hours from our location. On this occasion, we bring Beca with us to your home. The purpose of this visit is to meet face to face, for you to meet Beca, for us to evaluate your fenced in yard, and if there are other dogs in the home to evaluate the dog to dog interaction. There is no compromise on your part to adopt and neither is there a compromise on our part to adopt her out to you. If we determine that you are the best candidate for his adoption and you are interested in proceeding with the adoption we complete the adoption contract, collect the adoption fee, and provide you with her Veterinary records. We will not adopt out any of our dogs to a household where there is no fenced-in-yard (it does not have to be big, just fenced in) or where electric fences are in use.

Meet Grace this girl has a second chance at life. She went through a very extensive expensive surgery to repair her heart valve stenosis, they placed a balloon in her heart. animal.description:
Meet Lady! 

SENIOR LOVERS!...Meet Prince & Lady! They were pulled from a rural southern shelter in July after their owners surrendered them because they were moving. They are a bonded pair who always look after each other. They eat together, they walk together, and they chill together. They are very relaxed and well behaved.  They just need a quiet retirement home to live out their golden years. Their ideal home is one with no cats and no little kids. November is adopt a senior month so why not adopt this beautiful Shepard duo who are still looking for their FURever home?

Interested in meeting Lady? 

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Our process is as follows:
1.  Review our policies and adoption radius  on our website: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/
2.  Submit an application for review and approval;
3.  MPM Rescue reviews application and checks vet records and references;
4.  MPM foster contacts approved applicant(s) to arrange a home check and meeting with available dog(s);
5.   If there is a good fit, adoption is completed with a contract and fees (payable via check or cash).

The adoption fee is listed here: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/

Dogs from Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Age appropriate vaccinations
- Heartworm test (for dogs over 6mo) and treatment if positive
- Microchip
- Deworming
- Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

*Please note that the identified breed(s) are best guesses. We very rarely have information on our dogs' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays.*

animal.description:
Meet Mimi - A wonderfully sweet Lab/Dane/Mastiff Mix (just a guess on breeds) who is 9 years old and 120 lbs. This beautiful senior girl is pretty much as close to perfect as any dog could be! She is super sweet, gentle and spends her days relaxing. She would make a wonderful companion to any lucky adopter. She is low energy and although she enjoys walks, she loves to be inside hanging by her fosters side. She's a wonderful girl in the house; she's housetrained and has great house manners! Mimi would love all the attention to herself so she needs to be an only dog in the home. If you're looking for an easy, sweet and low key companion, look no further. Mimi is perfect!

Mimi was surrendered to the shelter by her owner because they could not care for her properly. Mimi is so very sweet and just wants to be with people and in the air conditioning. :) Mimi does well on the leash and rides well in the car. Mimi is not fostered with children, so for this reason, if there are children in her forever home they should be respectful kids 6 years and up. Mimi is spayed, up to date on vaccines, on monthly preventatives and microchipped.

The adoption fee for this dog is $250 which includes routine vetting and spay/neuter. ***Please note that our first step is submitting an application (it does not commit you in any way but allows us to discuss with you if you and the dog are a good fit).

In addition, an important step in approving adoption applicants is to complete a vet check. Vetting of current and past pets is very important to us, thus we will be speaking with the vet(s) listed on your application to ensure that your current and previous pet(s) are kept up to date on vaccines (including rabies), spayed or neutered, maintained on appropriate monthly preventatives and examined annually by your vet.***

If you would like to meet Mimi , please fill out our online application by clicking HERE and then email Kim at KLarimerLovepaws@gmail.com

If you are viewing this on PetFinder or other venue , please go to our website at www.lovepawspg.org

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Niko is such a happy dog! Our best guess on breed is maybe pit bull terrier and beagle (?) He is crate and house trained, doing very well with both. He has a lot of energy and loves outside time. Niko likes to PLAY HARD, especially with another canine buddy. He *may be* a little too rough for younger children. We suggest children OVER the AGE OF 8, unless your kiddos are super tough and don't mind getting playfully pushed over by him. Niko is super soft and snuggly and will make an awesome dog for the RIGHT family. Could that be you?

Our first step is an application which can be filled out at: www.cvrrescue.org

The adoption fee for this dog is $175.00 which helps to cover a portion of the care provided, including: spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm testing, deworming, age appropriate vaccinations: DHLP/P, Bordetella, Rabies, and any medical care received while with CVRR. All animals are on flea/tick and parasite prevention for the duration of foster care.

CVRR is a nonprofit organization, we have no paid staff. Applications are reviewed and processed by our volunteers. Please be patient and understand that it takes an average of 7-14 days to process the applications including reference checks and follow-up questions. You can expedite the process by providing phone and email info for all your references.

Once yo my ur application is approved, we will schedule a meet-and-greet to see if the dog picks you too. If it seems the adoption will be a good match for all, there is an adoption fee and an adoption contract to be signed. The adoption fee helps to cover a portion of the care provided to the animals. By the time of adoption all dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vetting.

CVRR is a NO KILL rescue organization and we have a LIFETIME COMMITMENT to all of our animals. If for any reason the adoption does not work out the animal is to be returned to CVRR. We will re-evaluate and choose a new home based on the best fit for that particular animal. 2/2/21 11:33 AM

animal.description:
BACKSTORY:
Late on a Friday night we got a message from a rescue friend asking if we had room for a 6-month-old pup, the owner reached out to her but they didn’t have a foster home available. The next day we contacted the owner to get all the details and our hearts were heavy as we could hear the sorrow in his voice. He was having to surrender a pup he’s had since he was a baby due to housing circumstances beyond his control. He didn’t want him in a cage at animal control, he wanted him in a home so rescue was his best shot. We put out a plea to our fosters and within minutes we had a transport team and a foster coordinated.

EDUCATION:
* Sit
* Paw
* Touch
* Higher energy
* House trained

ACTIVITIES THIS CUTIE ENJOYS:
* Treats: Whimzies, fish skins, wild weenies, hot dogs if you remove the casing
* Food: can be a bit picky
* Toys: hard chews and anything that makes noise
* Walks: pulls hard at the beginning but eases up, pulls when he sees something he's interested in
* Playing with toys
* Going on walks
* Shoulder blade scratches

SKILLS:
* Dogs: overexcited, rough and tumble player
* Kids: 10+, he is a bull in a china shop
* People: takes time to warm up
* Cats: unknown

CHALLENGES:
* Learning to love his crate
* Not a fan of the vacuum, doorbell, and loud noises
* Normal puppy behaviors like chewing and mouthiness
* He enjoys singing the song of his people.. he's a barker.
* He doesn't realize how big he is

animal.description:
LOCATION: MILO POINT RICHMOND 

Lily is an active, full-throttle kind of girl! Grab life by the horns and run with it... leading the way! She is super confident, a bit bossy, and selective about the company she keeps. Lily isn't a social butterfly, she would love a home with a couple active adults who don't have a ton of social activity in the home. She will protect, and maybe get possessive if allowed, so best to keep some boundaries with her! Smart, athletic girl who needs dog savvy folks with a yard and time to provide lots of love, activity and ongoing training and stimulation.
She doesn't love crowds, so no dog parks for Lily.
 
Experienced dog-savvy applicants ONLY. 

Thank you for considering adoption of a Milo Foundation Sanctuary dog. Our Sanctuary is where our rescued dogs who have had difficulty in a home in the past, have behavioral issues, or too much energy, or for some, aggression issues with other dogs, or intense stranger danger that make them more difficult to safely and happily live in urban environments. These are not beginner dogs or for the most part nor are they for families with children. IF you are looking for an easy dog to add to your family, we suggest looking at the dogs at our Adoption Center, Milo Pt Richmond. BUT, if you can offer a safe and nurturing home to a dog with some behavioral "quirks" please do send an application today. Thank you.

animal.description:
Shelly is a captivating, intelligent and affectionate 4-year old, 55 lb. girl who is looking for her forever family. 

Since she was saved from the NYCACC and in foster for a few months, Shelly is now fully house trained, knows her basic commands, and is following leash instructions like come close, look, find it, and other tricks. She is also quiet and well-behaved in the home, including when left alone.

Since Shelly is very food motivated and eager to eat her meals, she gets fed from food dispensers requiring work or smarts to retrieve the food (puzzle bowls/toys, snuffle mats, etc.).

Shelly will do best in a home with active adults (older children, ok) and no other pets as she is she is unpredictable toward other dogs and has a prey drive for small animals. However, due to her obedience training, she has learned to tolerate passing by other dogs when out on walks/jogs. If a backyard is part of her furever home, it should have a secure fence.

“Shelly is a sweet, affectionate girl who loves to be pet by everyone, including strangers she meets on walks,” says her foster mom.  “And people frequently remark on how beautiful she is!”

Shelly is spayed, vaccinated, and microchipped.

To learn more about Shelly, please contact AmsterDog at info@amsterdog.org or fill out our application at www.amsterdog.org/application to get the process started.

Thank you for caring about a pet in need!

animal.description:
Skye - 3 y/o Female Terrier Mix - 35 lbs | currently in boarding | Cinnaminson, NJ

*** BEHAVIORIST / TRAINER WILL PROVIDE INTENSIVE INSTRUCTION/GUIDANCE TO ANYONE WHO CAN COMMIT TO 3-6 MOS OF IN-HOME FOSTERING ***


Skye is a little 3 y/o, 35 lb. female terrier mix that was saved from euthanasia at the shelter in Philly. 

Skye knows basic commands, is house trained, and crate trained. She loves cuddling, playing with her Kong and other chew toys, and peanut butter.

*But* she also becomes very protective of her “person” after she settles in and becomes comfortable and has shown to lunge at and nip/bite others as a result. She has been abandoned and given away so many times that her biggest fear is losing anyone that shows her love and kindness of any kind.

She is also highly reactive to other animals so she must go to a single-pet home, with no children, and a very experienced person willing to work with her and provide the training and behavior modification she needs under the intensive direction of a behaviorist/trainer for a period of 3-6 mos.
 
There must be someone out there who will see this sweet little girl as the diamond in the rough that she is and show her she need not fear being abandoned ever again.

----------------------------------

If you are able to help us help Skye, please contact AmsterDog at info@amsterdog.org or fill out our application at www.amsterdog.org/application to get the process started.

Thank you for caring about a pet in need!

animal.description: Jake Ryan could be compared to a fluffy teddy bear - he has a soft coat that's great to snuggle up with and he'll always be there for you when you need him! Some of Jake's favorite things besides snuggling are eating treats, watching tv, exploring new places and playing fetch. He's great at catching the ball and will even bring the ball back to you (most of the time). Then when it's time to relax, Jake is happy to oblige, rolling over on his back for belly-rubs, his tail happily wagging. Between his amazing smile and his goofy antics, Jake is guaranteed to brighten your day. He loves being with his friends, is eager to please and he'll never turn down a treat, knowing he needs to get into a 'sit' for his reward. In addition to being a volunteer favorite, Jake has made a lot of doggie friends, too, and had a blast on a recent sleepover with one of his canine pals. Jake is also thriving in APA!'s Total Obedience Program (TOP), which is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As a TOP dog, Jake has a personalized training plan and works with a volunteer trainer several times a week to help him learn the skills to become the best dog he can be! Jake is learning skills like sit and down, walking nicely on leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers or other dogs, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' coming when called and 'place', which means Jake will go to a specific place in your home on command. Once Jake successfully completes all the skills on his training plan, he will be considered TOP Dog Ready! Jake is working hard to become a wonderful companion, and as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with him after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https://vimeo.com/89434193 Jake Ryan is currently accepting applications for forever homes, although households with little kiddos or cats need not apply. But if you're looking for a steady companion that you can bring on your adventures, look no further and come on down and meet handsome Jake Ryan!

animal.description:
This gorgeous girl is 3 year-old Twix.  Twix is a sweet girl who just needs a little time to warm up to you!  She was rescued from a hoarding situation and has some skin conditions that need managing, but she was recently spayed and is otherwise a healthy girl.  Twix is approximately 50 pounds, so she is just large enough to make a great foot warmer and just small enough that you can lift her into the car!

Twixie is a very sweet dog who loves belly rubs, kisses, and sticking her head out the car window.  When she is excited, she snorts like a little pig!  It’s so cute!  She needs a little bit of patience and a little bit of space, but she will be following you around in no time!

Twix is really good on the leash and usually walks at your pace without pulling.  She will sometimes freeze up when she sees strange people or dogs, so she might prefer to go on walks at a time when there are fewer people out.  Stairs can be a little intimidating, but she’s tough and she has made a lot of progress!  We’re still working on some basic commands like sitting and coming when called. She recognizes her name now and will sometimes come when called, but she does get distracted easily.  

Twix really loves her treats and they can help get her attention, but sometimes she can’t pass up looking at all the people and cars going by!  She is comfortable napping and relaxing in her crate when the door is open - we leave it open because she also loves our couch! - so we think she could be fully crate-trained pretty quickly.  She does have quite a bit of separation anxiety though and will need to work on staying on her own.

We think Twix would probably do best in a house without other dogs or small children because she is sometimes afraid of dogs coming near her while on her walks and small children making noise seem to scare her.  She hasn’t been around cats or small animals before.  She is interested in insects though and will try to get rid of all the flies in the house!

Please help us get Twix into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!

If you would like to adopt or foster this loving dog Twix, please fill out an application at www.passionforpitties.com under the “Adorable Adoptables” heading.

animal.description:
My name is Asifa,

    I am a rescue from Kuwait about 8 years ago. To a pack of nomadic, wild dogs roaming the desert, I was born on a Camp before being rescued and bought to the U.S. at 4 months old. I got my name from a Kuwaiti friend which means “Organizer”. I do have Shepard in my DNA so naturally I do like organization and daily activity. 

I have long, black thick hair with a curly tail and weigh 75 lbs. with a charming and loving personality.

I LOVE to be with people, in the middle of all the action. Walking, jogging, car rides, running in the yard and all the attention you can give me, I do have a lot of energy.

I love to sleep close to you by the bed, but will occasionally get up to check things around the house and come right back. I'm a great watchdog.

Not too fond of other dogs but with some patience, time, and slow introductions, I will accept one. I lived with a couple of  other companions before and learned they can be my friends.

I can be vocal and bark at anyone that comes around the house or through my yard, just to let everyone know I am on guard. But accept all visitors happily once my owner lets me know all is ok. I Love to chase all other animals away though that includes, squirrels, deer, and have chased a small fox that came too close to our house once.

I am beautiful and UNIQUE. I talk a lot with hush like bark just to get your attention, especially if I need water, or would like us to go out and do something.

Night time I like my dog treat, will roam around the house checking up on things, like to be where I can see outside and make sure all is good. I will sleep close to you, esp at the foot of the bed on MY bed.

I will love and trust you with all the loyalty I can give, just give me attention, include me in activities, and let me know I am doing good by you and you will see I am a loyal companion and just want to be a family member too.
   I am spayed, had my vaccines,  heartworm neg.   and very  healthy.  I am the perfect dog , friend , companion for the right home .  Everyone loves me because i'm so smart and loyaI also I  love to walk.  We can exercise together. .Everything you want!  Come and say hello.


-------------------------------------------
from owner 
I wish time was different but I am looking for a beautiful active  family to take her in, Asifa has too much energy, requires a lot of attention, affection, activity and difficult for us at this time to give her everything she desires.


I love her a GREAT deal and only want the best for her and a family with  older kids  or teens who  can provide her with more attention., more active life and more of the love she craves.

  she must have a fenced yard, no electric fences, No cats.  email for an application Laura@RoadHomeRescue.com
 no phone calls. we do a trial foster period.  a meet and greet once approved

 more pixs to come.  This is a beautiful ,special dog who needs  an exceptional home.  We had a trainer work with her so she walks well  on  a leash and listens to your commands,.   she will be loyal and devoted. if interested let me know and I can set up a chat with her guardian.

animal.description:
If interested in this dog, complete the application in link below.

Buddy is 2 1/2 years old and was rescued from being an outside dog left alone in backyard.

From foster dad.

What makes your foster delightful/special? Very protective and attentive to owner. Obeys commands and will wait for approval. Loves to run and play. Fond of his toys especially tennis balls and his "Wubba". Goes to his crate on request and will stay overnight 7-8 hours. He loves attention.

Cute things your foster does that could be endearing or a personality point that would make people
want to meet him/her? Obedient and kind when he gets know you. Great protector.

What kinds of routines and activities does your foster like most? He likes to go on walks and rides in
the car. Really likes to play with his toys and be chased.

He seems to be okay with female dogs and smaller
males. It took some getting used to but he gets along okay with our Himalayan cat.

Is your foster OK with cats (are they living w/cats now? Describe how they behave around cats): At first
he tested boundaries but our cat did not in give him and even though the cat does not have claws,
Buddy gives him space. He will on occasion give chase but has never fought with our cat.

Describe THE ideal home for your foster? Someone who likes to play with dogs. A good sized fencedmyard. Not too social.

Adoption fee $350

To apply to foster, foster to adopt or adopt , please fill out app at

https://www.heidislegacydogrescue.com/application

Thank you for completing the application. We are all volunteers and short on time, we will contact you back only if we have more questions or your application is approved and you will be invited to meet the dog. We apologize for not being able to answer everyone back.

For more information contact Lenore.d@heidislegacydogrescue.com

DOGS Are in Foster Homes. There is no shelter.

**Our companions MUST live in your home as part of your family.**We do not transport.

animal.description:
Tulip is a sweet, active Rottweiler who came from animal control, so we have no history on her.  She is small for a Rottweiler.  She weighs about 55 lbs.

Tulip is very gentle and sweet. She is a happy girl who loves to play.  She definitely prefers male dogs over female dogs.  She plays rough but she isn't aggressive.  She enjoys going for short walks, but she isn't a long walker or hiker.  Her foster parents exercise her by throwing a ball for her in an enclosed tennis court once a day and that's enough for her.  She is housebroken and crate trained.  She wouldn't do well being left alone all day in a crate, but she's fine if left for a few hours here and there.  

Tulip is not as comfortable with men as she is with women.  She will not approach men she does not know and won't interact with them until she learns to trust them.  Some men she just never warms up to.  We don't think she would do well in a home with only men.  

Tulip has been spayed, fully vaccinated and microchipped.

Tulip's adopter must live within an hour's drive of Atlanta.  We always do a home visit before an adoption.  Tulip's adoption fee is $250.

animal.description:
Dawson is a nerd. He is a 5 year old, barely knee-high meatball weighing in at 75 pounds. He is obviously a pit bull and he is hard to place because he's a pit bull. I can't claim he's a suave George Clooney type, or rippling in hotness like a Jason Momoa, but he has his charms. Let's talk about them.

This dog LOVES toys. He loves to run and play. He loves to romp and toss his toys in the air. He would sell his soul for a tennis ball and he will bring it back to you every. single. time. He loves to give kisses to his people and he is the most affectionate dog ever. He is well-mannered and very people social. I have attached video of him singing with an 8 year old girl. He is incredibly sweet and lovely. 

On the downside, he's never going to be good with all dogs. He has his friends but we never know who he will like and who he won't, so he have decided needs to be an only dog. He's also no cat. In the interest of strict honesty, he farts like a demon and could clear a room. He needs a home with a fenced yard and people who appreciate a snorty, low-riding fat boy. 

This dog survived Hurricane Dorian and a pretty crappy life before that, and someone out there wants a knee high dog to be their love and companion.  If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/ and then email nicole@bigfluffydogs.com. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

ROSIE (female)
Breed: German Shepherd

Rosie was found tied to a shopping cart in a Walmart parking lot. She's approx. 2 years old. She's a typical shepherd.... smart, affectionate with humans, vocal and a bit bossy. She's been fine with dogs we have introduced her to but there is no way we can say how she would do with your mother in laws dog, it would depend on her dog, proper introduction, etc. We do not have children nor has she met any while in our care but we have no reason to believe she wouldn't be fine with children. Most of our dogs are from local LA area shelters, we generally have no prior history for them.
Adoption fees vary between $350 - $450 for puppies 8 weeks - 5 years, $350 6 - 9 years and $250 for dogs over 9 years. Adoption fee covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip a wellness check, any additional medical expenses necessary and of course the all the love and daily care we take with each dog before they are adopted.

She is such a sweet girl, she is living with other dogs now in her foster home and does great with them.  It will take Nancy some time to warm up to her new home so it will take someone with patience until she comes around.  Once she does she doesn't want to leave your side. She is house trained and good on a leash, she does better with a harness. If you are able to give this girl love and a forever home please:

 contact us @ adoptions@emilysfriendsrescue.com  


 
The money collected covers any medical treatments the dog may have had while in our care.  All  of our dogs are altered (spayed/neutered), have had all shots (age  appropriate in the case of puppies) including Bordetella (kennel cough),  rabies, and the distemper/parvo series. Dogs have been heart worm  screened and are heart worm negative, have had a clear fecal exam and  are up to date on Frontline and Heartgard. Adopters  will receive copies of all vet records, rabies certification, and tags.  The adoption fee also covers all transport and health certificate costs  we incur. Dogs from out of state travel on USDA inspected humane,  healthy, & sanitary animal transport professionals. 
Disclaimer:  Please note that the breeds posted on our dogs' biographies are our  best guess based on years of working with rescue dogs. Adopters who need  to know the exact breed or mix of breeds of a particular dog must have  the dog's DNA tested at their own expense.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Bliss. I was found as a stray in Coachella Valley, and taken to a local shelter. The shelter tried finding my owners, but nobody came forward to claim me, and I didn't have any potential adopters. The rescue coordinator contacted this shelter to take me in because I was put on the euthanasia list when I showed "aggression" toward a new dog that was supposed to be my new kennel mate. Since I have been here (Came in January 2020), I have been more outgoing, social, and accepting of most of the other dogs here. I definitely do not like cats, so it would be best I went to a home without any. The staff are working toward my behavior with other dogs, but would not label me as "dog aggressive" since I have not tried harming any other dogs. I do, like most other dogs, bark at other dogs through the fence, but have not tried to go after another dog outside of my kennel. I am cat aggressive, so I should not go to a home with cats. I love to chase and catch rabbits, mice, and squirrels, and I am a very good hunter!  I love to be loved on, cuddled, and love to nap. I started limping and walking funny one day, so the staff took me to the vet. I have 2 bad hips and 1 bad knee. I have osteoarthritis, as well as hip dysplasia. So, my bad knee, and both of my hips are bone to bone. The vet said due to my age, and breed, surgery is not a good option for me. I just need to rest and live out the rest of my life in a calm and loving environment. I am on medication, which is pretty affordable, but I need it to help control my pain. I have been in a foster home since March, and they have labeled me as a lovable couch potato! I am pretty low maintenance, and just want to relax most of the day. I have had little to no accidents inside the house. I would love to find a home with a family who will love and cuddle me. I am not an escape artist, but I can jump a 6 foot fence if left alone. If you have any questions, or would like to meet me outside of my kennel, please ask staff.
                                                            Love,
                                                               Bliss

animal.description:
Meet Bunny! 
-----
4-7 years old
40-50 lbs
Vaccinated
-----

Bunny was at the shelter for a week with no care and no chance due to a "rescue only" label. She was labeled with severe aggression and had massive tumors on her belly from what looked like breeder neglect. She was miserable and afraid. Thanks to the help and support of her sponsor, Kaley Cuoco, we were able to rescue this beautiful girl. 
Once Bunny gained some weight, she was spayed and had surgery to remove several cancerous tumors, as well as dental work. When the tumor test results came back, we found out that poor Bunny has hemangiosarcoma, a very aggressive type of cancer. She doesn't have a long time to live but has already out lived the time frame given by doctors and doesn't look to be giving up any time soon! This girl is a fighter with a zest for life. She is active and alert. Loves her walks and loves play time. And even though she has few teeth left, she LOVES her bully sticks and other chew treats. 
Due to her condition we are hoping to get her into a forever home to live out her final days/weeks/months, being loved on by a family. Something every dog should get to experience. 
Bunny is dog aggressive so her ideal home would have no other pets. She is sweet with all humans. Though she has not been around kids, we would expect her to be great with them too.

Hi, my names is Mike and my foster Mom says I am a 9 year old GEM!  I love to sleep late, take naps, snore loudly, watch too much TV AND am a HUGE fan of cheese and peanut butter!  I am a calm guy who is very comfortable at home on the couch I am equally happy to look outside or be in the yard sunbathing and napping in the fresh air.  I am an easy going cuddle bug whether on the couch or in a bed but I am also happy and confident enough to be on my own.  I walk nicely on a leash but may need some breaks in the walk because I can get tired.  I am free to roam in my foster home but easily goes into my crate and am quiet while there.  I LOVE all humans, big and small and am a gentle soul.  I am looking for my furever home with my furever person/persons/family and look forward to meeting you ALL!  If you are interested in meeting me, please send an email or fill out a pre adoption application and a CDR volunteer will get back to you just as quick as they can!
Cuddles and kisses-Mike




**The ADOPTION FEE for this pet is $400-450.00,  which includes getting the puppy/dog up to date on rabies, distemper and bordetella vaccines, fecal test and deworming if necessary, heartworm test, spay or neuter (not including pre-surgical bloodwork) and a microchip. Free access to our weekly training classes is also included for the life of the dog, something no other rescue in the area offers.***

animal.description:
***Sage is not a CDR dog and has not been evaluated by CDR.  This is a courtesy posting for Sage's current guardian, who will make all decisions about her placement.  To apply for Sage, fill out an online application at http://cayugadogrescue.org/wp/adoption-process/ and the rescue folks will forward it to her current guardian!  

Hello! My name is Sage, and I am incredibly sweet and playful girl who loves being outside and exploring new things!

Quick Facts:

Breed: German Shepherd/Lab mix
Gender: Female, spayed
Age: 3 1/2 years old
Size: 62 pounds
Good with…
Dogs?   I'm scared of dogs I don't know! (see more below)
Cats? Not sure
Kids? Yes! 7+ years

History
We adopted Sage in April from a shelter in Tennessee where she had been for about 3 months after being surrendered by her previous owner. We don’t know much about her previous life, other than that she was surrendered. She is awesome, we love her, but without a fenced yard, we are unable to keep her safe (see details below).  We hate to have to rehome her, she’s so wonderful, but want to be clear that it’s not her fault, we just don’t have the fenced yard situation that she requires for her safety.

Personality
Hi everyone!  I’m such a happy girl!  Everyone says that in addition to being absolutely beautiful, I am also incredibly sweet and am awesome at making new friends  with people and other dogs quickly!  I let everyone pet me (so nice!) and I sometimes give kisses when I am extra happy!  I like to hang out near my people and will often follow them from room to room, keeping an eye on things, seeing if anything interesting is happening.  I like to be next to them either on the floor or on a couch (when allowed)—but definitely in the same room.  For those who love to have a dog all over you, I have to warn you that I am not a huge snuggler.  This is very normal for shepherds and shepherd mixes-- we like to be close, but not right on top of you – which they tell me is perfect, because at 62 pounds, that would be a lot of dog on your lap!

I am such a friendly girl, completely housebroken and am very smart! I’ve learned a whole bunch of super fun commands like: sit, come, stay, shake, and off.  I am working on learning to not pull on the leash when I get excited or see a chipmunk-- they tell me this is a very high level ability and will take some time.  I love to learn, love positive reinforcement strategies, and love your attention and the treats that come my way when you teach me things! 
When I am not outside, I love to look out the window and watch the birds and critters, so I am hoping for an adopter who has a good view spot for me in the house!  So fascinating!! I also like to nap during the day on the floor or in my dog bed, and sometimes on the couch when I am allowed. I am very chill while indoors and only bark occasionally when a package is delivered or a garbage truck stops outside. 

I do some silly things…I bark a little bit when dreaming, I do a happy dance when it’s time to go for a walk, I will play fetch with a squeaky ball and tug with a rope toy until the end of time,  and I am a huge fan of ice cubes!  Really!  When I hear the ice maker making cubes, I run into the kitchen and sit excitedly until somebody gives me one!

I absolutely LOVE being outside and running around – FAST! A house with a big fenced in yard is essential for me! I don’t like being tied to a lead in the yard, and have figured out how to escape from collars and harnesses when I really want to--even when they are on me nice and snug--and once I wriggle out, I can’t help but to GO-GO-GO!  Which obviously isn’t safe for me--there have been some close calls and we don’t want any more of those.  I love going for hikes, walks and runs on leash, so here's the deal with those things.  I never try to wriggle out of my collar or harness when running/jogging with you, so that’s safe.  On hikes and walks on leash, you need to pay attention to the presence of bunnies (my biggest weakness) and other critters, and when you see me spin around and try to pull hard (that’s my method of getting out of the collar or harness), just grab me quick and hold onto me until the bunny or critter is gone.  And please watch the doors, as I could sneak out really fast if someone is coming or going and I spy something outside that is irresistible.  

Cohabitation
I currently live with 2 children, ages 7 and 10 and am very sweet and gentle with them.

I am sweet and friendly with the few dogs in my neighborhood whom I know and trust.  With them, I wag and play bow and act very friendly.  I am however very scared of dogs whom I don't know.  With them, I will be very barky and spazzy and lunge and make a big fuss because I am just very scared.  So, I need to go at a very slow, careful pace when meeting other dogs.  If there is a dog in your house already, would be best if it was a calm, smaller, sweet and friendly dog who would give me the space I need until we can become friends.  I seem to feel most comfortable with smaller, calm, male dogs. 

I have not been around any cats so we aren’t sure if I like them or not. I’d be glad to have a meet and greet with any potential fur-siblings!

Favorite Activities
•	Playing fetch with a squeaky ball!
•	Running around outside!
•	Being scratched behind my ears!
•	Hiking, Running, Walking!
•	Chilling near my humans!
•	Gazing out the window!
•	Being brushed!
•	Chomping on ice cubes

Why I am looking for a new home
I really need a home that has a large, secure, fenced in yard for me to explore and run around in.  My current family has tried a dog lead as well as an electric collar for me to be outside and I have cleverly learned to escape any harness and collar and have found that the reward of running free is greater than the risk of the electric fence collar. I have escaped frequently and my humans fear for my safety each time.  I am learning emergency recall training and do EXCELLENT with it indoors or when attached to my lead and under supervision but I am unable to come back once I have escaped and am out running free.

Medical
All shots are up-to-date.  No medical issues that we are aware of.

Summary
I will make the most wonderful forever dog to someone who will take me on hikes and walks, play fetch with me, and let me run free in a big, fenced in yard! I truly am such a love and incredibly smart, I just need to find the right forever family so that I can be safe and happy and live my very best life!

If you are interested in adopting me, fill out an online application at http://cayugadogrescue.org/wp/adoption-process/ and the rescue folks will forward it to my current guardian!

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO ON THIS DOG BEFORE REQUESTING AN APPLICATION.  MANY OF OUR DOGS HAVE STRICT REQUIREMENTS FOR THEIR ADOPTION.

4 year old female Chihuahua, about 5 pounds. Little Miss Priya! She is shy and sweet. She is quiet unless you leave her alone and she will howl to let you know you forgot her (don't worry it doesn’t last long). Her tongue is often hanging out from her tiny underbite. She'll sit on her hind legs and beg you to share, only to bring it to her friend Binde (my adopted Smidget). Priya needs to learn more about life and that it's not so scary to be a dog. She needs a human that will love on her but also not baby or carry her around all the time. She needs to learn to dog and her past life didn’t seem to teach her that skill. Crate training has helped support her in knowing she's ok to be in the same room and not be held. She will need to have another confident doggie companion who will help her build confidence and show her that strangers and moving cars aren't so scary while on a walk or out in public. She is great in the car and will look to you for reassurance. She is fine with cats, other dogs, and older children (foster brother is very dog savvy 7 year old and she comes with us to daycare and is okay with all the kids fully supervised). Priya is shy but once she warms up she will be right next to you at your feet or in your lap. She can have a bit of a sensitive tummy so a consistent diet of a food with no chicken is ideal. Watch out though, she is mischievous and will jump on the table, the counter, and sniff for stuff to get into, if she can. She's a tiny girl but the sweetest attitude that needs a home to build her confidence in this big world! 

Adoption contract and fee applies.  All adoptable dogs can be met at adoption events hosted every weekend. For a list of scheduled events go to: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/events .  Smidget Rescue is not a shelter, and dogs cannot be seen at the Rescue location. All dogs are fostered throughout the Puget Sound area and are brought to the events where they can be met by prospective adopters. Additional pictures of adoptable dogs can be seen at: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/photos_stream?tab=photos_albums.   All adoptable dogs are spayed or neutered at 6 months of age or older, and always before being placed in their new homes.  APPLICATIONS CAN BE OBTAINED BY EMAIL ONLY. Adoption process includes application, meet & greet, home visit and reference check. Email Jamie at smidgetrescue@hotmail.com or click on the CONTACT link on this page.  PLEASE DOUBLE CHECK YOUR EMAIL ADDRESS BEFORE SENDING.  We get a fair number of incorrect emails and Jamie is not able to contact potential adopters.  Notice:  We do not ship dogs out of state.  If you live within a five-hour radius of Seattle, WA, (such as Portland, Vancouver B.C., etc.), we can arrange for a home visit.  If your home seems like a great fit for the dog you would like to adopt, you must then drive to meet the dog at one of our weekend events or at the fosters home.
