animal.description:
Sammy came to us after his mom could no longer care for her due to her own health issues. It was an upsetting situation for all but she found comfort knowing that her little baby would be safe and sound with a new forever family.
Here is what is foster mom has to say about our little Sammy:
"Sammy is a sweet old man, with a little quirk. He does not like it when someone reaches out to pet or touch him. His lets you know this by giving a bark. He does like to cuddle, just on his own terms. He loves when his person lays on the floor so he can come to them for his pets. Once his person is on the floor, he will lay next to them and nuzzle, and allow petting and touching.
Oddly, he allows me to pick him up with no issues. He does not jump up on furniture, and doesn't seem to enjoy sitting on the couch with you (when he's picked up and placed up there). He will play with toys as long as you're willing to play with him.
Sammy is a Velcro dog. He wants to be near his person at all times. He likes to be right at your feet. If you get up, he will also get up to follow you. He sleeps in his open crate (in an enclosed area) through the night. He has no issues with eating and easily takes his medications twice a day in pill pockets. He is potty trained, but it took a few days for him to understand where it was, and wasn't, ok to go.
Sammy has some pain and mobility issues. A house with no stairs would most likely be best for him. The vet has him taking medications twice a day to help with pain.
He's a very good boy that seems to get along with all people and dogs. He just needs someone who understands the perils of growing old, and who's willing to take care of his medical and medication needs."

Maggie is a sweet girl who gets along with people and other dogs. We do not know what she thinks of cats. This pretty girl still has some puppy energy and would love a family to go hike or do things with as well as continue some more consistent basic training. Her energy may be too much for young/small children. Maggie is about 2-3 years old and 45 pounds. Please help Maggie find the loving home she deserves.

We do NOT ship our animals. All adoptive families must travel to us to meet their adoptive dog/cat. Applicants must live within a 2 hour radius from Sparta/Andover (07871/07821).

animal.description: Hi there! My name is Ruffalo. animal.description:
My name is Thunderbolt! I'm a 10 year old beagle and I'm currently weighing in at 26 pounds. I'm still trying to adjust to the indoor life and understand how I'm supposed to be a pet dog. You see, my entire life I have lived outdoors in a pen with only an igloo and had never seen a vet. I'm told I have some health issues starting with being diagnosed Heartworm positive Stage 2, have slight arrhythmia, an ear infection and my mouth hurts. The only good part of my teeth hurting is that I get only soft dog food and soft treats. I'm really getting used to sleeping the day away in the dog bed I have picked out and also started sleeping in the human's bed between them. I can sleep the entire night away - no worries there! I love simply being touched and petted and really like being near you, even though I'm still unsure what all this means.

Here's a little info: I am not house trained but I am crate trained. I enjoy being around other dogs - it's kind of crazy at my foster house because I've been around 7 other dogs and we all like each other. I really just kind of observe them and every once in a while I'll follow them. If anyone goes to the kitchen - I manage to get myself up pretty quick to see if I can get some food or at least some crumbs. I'm just starting to learn about being held and sitting in a lap, not too sure about all that yet. With a little more time I might be alright with the idea.

I still have to be neutered and I have to go through heartworm treatment because no one cared enough about me to give me a monthly prevent. Give me some time to heal and I will be ready to go home with you. Let's go ahead and mark our calendars and pencil me in for mid-November/early December. I'll wait for you if you wait for me.

I would love to meet my new family soon, I've been waiting for you. If you would like to meet me, please submit an adoption application for me today!

Thank you for checking out my bio, please check back for an update. My life was saved recently and we are getting me safe and warm. Information will be updated as soon as I get settled in at my foster home.

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

animal.description:
Adoption Fee:  $150
Fostered in Baton Rouge, Louisiana
Age: 10 years
Weight: 5.4 lbs.

12/15/20 - Blitzen had a recheck for his ear and other than an ear infection which is being treated, he seems to be healing quite nicely.  Also, the results came back and the mass was benign.  Yay!

The doctor did find that his thyroid levels were off, so started Blitzen on Thyroxine, 1 mg. - 1/2 pill twice daily.  He is now feeling great!

11/28/20 - Blitzen had his surgery yesterday to remove the tumor in his right ear.  The mass was sent to the lab.  He is doing well.  He has a recheck scheduled for December 10th.  Thank you so much for your prayers and donations for sweet little Blitzen and he hopes everyone had a Happy Thanksgiving.

11/19/20 - Blitzen saw the specialist today at MedVet Mandeville for his ear.  His appointment was originally set for October 29th, but had to be cancelled because of the weather at that time.  He is scheduled for November 27 to have the tumor(s) removed and biopsied.  The estimate for his surgery is $1,741.59.  Please help with his surgery cost if you can and say prayers that everything goes well.

Thank you.

10/26/20 - Blitzen's consultation with the specialist is Thursday, 10/29/20.  We will update after this appt.

10/25/20 - Blitzen's foster mom has notice that his ears have been having a foul order and bothering him so she had them look into this today while he was under anesthesia being neutered.  It seems this poor baby has a 2 tumors down in his ear that need to be removed.  We are scheduling an appointment with a specialist at MedVet to have this done soon.

Please keep him in your prayers.

7/26/20 – Hi, it’s me, Blitzen again checking in.  Foster mom has found out that even though they named me Blitzen, (after a reindeer since my legs are a little longer), you can pretty much call me whatever you want since I can’t hear.  Yep, I’m pretty deaf.  Don’t feel sorry for me though, I think this is a real advantage.  You know how you have those annoying siblings, parents, and friends that talk too much or too loud and you wish they would just hush?  You know where I’m going with this don’t you? Lol  I cannot hear them.  ?  The down side is I can’t hear the ones I truly love.  But I can look at you adoringly and watch you speak to me and wag my tail.

Now, I can see, love, eat, play and everything else a normal dog can do.  One thing I am great at right now is humping my bed.  Yea, I know, not the most attractive thing, but we are all hoping that once I get neutered and some of these male hormones are gone, I won’t want to molest my blankets and bedding.  The good thing is that I don’t do that to my fur-siblings or anything else. 

The vet said that I can be neutered and get my dental as soon as I put a little more weight on.  Seems I was pretty much on the anorexic side when I got here and apparently that isn’t the “in” look any longer.  

I sleep good and eat my food like a champ (hard food mixed with a little water).  However, it seems I must have been given table scraps before because I am GREAT at begging.  I’m learning that these people aren’t as free with their food as the last people.  Well, I’m in a great home now, so I’ll learn to accept that.

Currently, I am an unaltered male, so I am marking, but foster mom has me wearing a belly band so I won’t mess up all the furniture.  Is that crazy?  A man of my age wearing a diaper!!  Oh well, who am I to fuss about it.  I’d much rather be here than where I came from.  Foster mom says that the marking will get better once I’m neutered.  Boy, getting neutered around here at this rescue seems to be a huge thing.    They are smart people, so it must be the thing to do.  No one else til now seemed to care, so I’m grateful.

Are you in the market for an older reindeer that does take naps, but still has energy, and is a sweetheart?  Well, stop right here, because Blitzen can be that man.

7/21/20 - Milo is settling into his foster home and we will post a bio soon updating on his medical status and personality.

7/13/20 - Yet another baby in desperate need of vetting, love, food and rescue.  A rescue friend contacted Yorkie Haven to see if we could help this poor baby.   Blitzen, as he is now called, was definitely in bad shape when we picked him up on Friday.  We went straight to the vet just to address the obvious issues, skin, ears, eyes, nail clip.  No matter that long nails are in for humans, they are NEVER in for dogs.

Sweet Blitzen received some ear medication and medicated shampoo.  As soon as he got home, they wild hair was cut off and he received his first soothing, medicated shampoo and massage.  He enjoyed it and the dirt that came off of him was ridiculous.  He felt better after getting out of the tub.  He ate supper like a champ.  You would too if you hip and back bones and ribs were poking out.  He had a very long, exhausting day and slept like a log.  Despite it all, Blitzen is a very resilient, happy boy.  We can't wait to see what he looks like in the weeks/months to come.  

Soon he will be neutered, get a much needed dental, receive his shots and get a microchip.  It's all uphill from here Blitzen  Don't look back and try to forget your past because the best is yet to come.
animal.name: Blitzen

Panda is a cute black and white boy whose markings really do look something like a panda bear. He is a young, strong, playful and loving Springer who is just finishing up his heartworm treatment.

In foster care, he has learned to sit on command and greet his foster mom with four paws on the floor. He does tend to be rough on bedding and pull out the stuffing, so he’d probably appreciate some more appropriate chew toys. Panda was an outside dog before rescue and is enjoying the great indoors these days. He is a good snuggler and a good watchdog. He seems to get along well with dog-savvy cats.

He will need an active adult family, dedicated to additional training, and a fenced yard. Because of the COVID 19 pandemic, Panda has not had many opportunities to get out and about. He is a strong boy who pulls on his leash and needs some practice meeting new people. He is smart and trainable and might excel at an active canine sport like agility. He has lots of energy and would make a willing jogging partner.

animal.description:
Date of birth: 5/9/2018

1/20/2021: Redmond is a cute American Staffordshire Terrier mix! He’s 2 years old and weighs 66 lbs. He’s playful and silly and lots of fun-- and he loves playing in the kiddie pool! 

• Redmond is very friendly and loves people. He also loves treats and is very food motivated. Redmond needs some work on his manners and plays a bit rough, so he’ll need a home without young kids.  

• Redmond gets along with some but not all dogs. He’s played nicely with some dogs in the yard here but we’ve found that it needs to be the right dog for it to work well. It would need to be another playful good natured dog who wouldn’t let Redmond get away with too much! If you have a dog who might be a good match for Redmond, you could bring your dog to meet Redmond to see if they could be buddies. 

• Redmond is not good with cats and must have a home without cats.

• We’d like to find Redmond a home with someone who has dog experience and knows how to work with a dog with some leash reactivity. Redmond can be leash reactive with some other dogs. A home with a wooden fence that’s fairly tall would be ideal.

• Unfortunately, Redmond tested positive fore heartworms. He’s had his first heartworm treatment already. He’ll need to keep to limited activity for the next several weeks while in the treatment phase, then he’ll be able to run and play like normal.  The treatments are done in our clinic and at no extra cost.  We can fill you in on his treatment plan if you are interested in fostering or adopting him.  

• Redmond was found as a stray and the poor guy had several lacerations on his nose and under his armpits. We’re not sure what caused them. He’s healed up now. He’s also been neutered, vaccinated and microchipped.

• He’ll be a good match for someone wanting an active, fun dog who’s a bit of a diamond in the “ruff”! 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE:  PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU.  Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info. 

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:
Email: christine@hsgkc.org
Phone: 913.521.2339
http://hsgkc.org

animal.description: Isn't he a handsome boy?! General is a large mature German Shepherd boy with a black saddle on a medium coat. He was found as an abandoned boy who was emaciated and suffering from an infestation of ticks & fleas on top of other skin issues. He is now a VERY healthy and gorgeous boy!  He is MOUTHY boy in that he loves 'to play with his mouth and large paws'. General has a loud bellowing voice to alert you to cars in the driveway/visitors but quiets down quickly if consoled that 'it's a welcome visitor!' He has some PTSD from previous abuse so a slow approach helps him to meet strangers [EX : don't run up an hug him, best to sit and extend a hand]. We recommend an experienced owner, and due to his large size, no young children. He is fine with non-aggressive other dog[s] as he LOVES to play. He is neutered, HW- & on preventatives, UTD on rabies and all of his shots!

animal.description:
Beautiful Jacqui is a 1 yr old, 28 lb Australian Shepherd mix.  Jacqui is sweet and affectionate and a loyal companion. She came to us in June looking for her new home.  Unfortunately, Jacqui developed Immune Mediated Polyarthritis (IMPA), an auto-immune disorder causing painful swollen joints.  Since June she has been going through medical treatment and is doing much better. Jacqui is now looking for that special person to call her own and give her the love and caring that she needs.  Please email uafdogs20@gmail.com to get more information on her condition and the care she will require.  Jacqui will need a home without others pets and a secure fenced yard. 


Our adoption fee of $150.00 helps cover expenses (vaccinations, spay/neuter, food, housing) for the homeless pets we rescue.  UAF does not ship our adoptables out of state and to ensure the best fit, UAF conducts a home visit to meet other pets and verify a safe, secure yard.

To start the process of adopting this dog or any other dog, please fill out our matchmaking form which can be accessed by copying the following address and pasting it into your browser.  Filling out this form does not obligate you to adopt.

https://www.unitedanimalfriends.org/index.php?option=com_rsform&view=rsform&formId=2

Please email uafdogs20@gmail.com to learn more about this dog.

animal.description:
WE WILL BE HOLDING ADOPTIONS ON SATURDAYS & SUNDAYS FROM 10-4 PM at our Adoption Center.  No appointments necessary.   Our adoption center is located next to CAL Ranch at 232 North Jones (I-95) Suite 170.    

Celestia is about   4 1/2  yrs old, born January 13,2016. She Loving. Cuddler.  Comes to whistle. Loves to run, rest and be a part of the group! Housebroken (mostly). Yes she is beautiful and magical! She is also extremely unique and needs only the perfect home.  Please read carefully. 

Commands: Sit (hand over head), wait (heel), down (lay down), off (off couch or high area), go pee (pee or poo). Will come to a whistle (with mouth) or come. 

Ideal Home: Needs to be with people 100% of the time.  Cannot be left alone. Must be with other large dog(s) or people. Family and multiple people with dogs is ideal.  Needs time hiking, outdoors, camping.  Needs to be walked at >1mile per day.  This is not a dog park,  dog.    She cannot be left alone at home ever in a crate or otherwise.  If you cannot provide this environment, she is not the right dog for you.  

She will not do well in apartments. No small yards. No cats. No small dogs.  She needs a house with big yard and doggie door

Do not leave Celeste unattended in a home.  Crate: Do not put Celeste in a crate. More will be known about me soon.   

A Path 4 Paws holds adoption events at our Adoptions Store,  located at 232 N. Jones Blvd, Suite 170  right next to CAL Ranch (North Jones/ I-95).   Please bring your dog(s) for a meet and greet (if applicable)  Please bring your entire family so everyone can meet. 

If you are interested in Celestia, please contact dogrescuelv@hotmail.com to confirm the dog you are interested in,  will be attending that particular event.  We have limited space at the store, therefore we can not take every dog out to the event.

Celestia is spayed/neutered, has current vaccinations and includes a microchip, deworming and 2 free vet visits.  Adoption fee applies.  Please make sure you have read the information listed on the homepage for requirements and restrictions. 

Foster homes & volunteers are always needed.  Please contact us regarding how you can help by fostering or volunteering for our organization.

animal.description:
Finn and his big smile are ready to find their forever home!  He is a 2 year old Shepherd mix and weighs about 45 pounds.  He is a busy, active boy that's always ready for an adventure. He loves hanging out with his humans and is a great walking/hiking buddy.  He's very playful with other dogs and enjoys car rides!  Finn will do best in a home with a female or non-dominant male dog that likes to play.  He will need a home with no cats and no children.

Finn shows anxiety in certain situations, so he was lucky enough to train with Loyal Companion K9 Academy to help set him up for future success.  He's looking for an active home that will continue with his training and understand his need for a predictable routine and consistent exercise.

Finn is neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines.  He is house trained and crate trained.  His adoption fee is $350.  For the chance to adopt Finn, please complete an application at happytailsaz.org.

Billie Jean is absolutely adorable! Billie Jean was rescued from Texas from overcrowded shelter.. she does have some neurological issues that the neurologist feels came from blunt force trauma... but she’s so amazingly sweet dispute what has happened to her.. She is in foster with another dog so we feel she would do best in a home with a big dog to help her as she loves to play with them and it helps her with her neurological issues... she does circle at times and seems to get very excited at feeding time but it’s all due to the neurological issues.. Billie Jean would do best in a home that has patience.. no little kids would be best.. but 10 and over is fine.. she loves to run in the backyard so a fenced in yard is best as long walks can be difficult for her at times.   

Could you be the one to offer this special sweetheart a loving forever home ??? Please apply at www.snarrnortheast.org

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 07/03/20
Reason for being in rescue: Owner release/owner was evicted
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? None noted

Weight: 25 lbs
Height: 18 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? No, but he would love to be able to fun in a fenced yard.

What kind of home would be best for me? Murphy is a family dog. He previously lived with 2 smaller dogs. He would absolutely like to have buddies in his home, but if the owner had time for him he could be an only dog. Murphy can be timid. He doesn't know much about being a pet. He needs a patient, experienced family that can show him the ropes of family life. Murphy is indifferent to cats.

What is my personality like? Murphy is a great dog who's had little experience in his short life. His young world has been turned upside down, he lost his home for no reason except his human ran into financial issues and couldn't keep her dog family. He does want to connect with people and will shyly look at you once he trusts you.

When you first meet Murphy, he is cautious but becomes friendly. He needs a little time to get to know you, then he desires being petted. Murphy is not happy in his crate and we believe his previous owner didn't crate train him. He will pant and drool and become incredibly stressed when he is crated. He is not a dog that can be left alone for long amounts of time during the day. He needs a lifestyle with a family where someone is home more than they are away.

We don't know about Murphy's interaction with children. He is happy and willing to work for a treat. We expect that he would be happy with mature children that are patient with him and give him time to warm up. Murphy does okay on a leash, he still needs work on his leash manners. Murphy is highly treat and food motivated and will absolutely work for treats. He has so much potential!

How do I act when I first meet new people? Cautious, then will warm up to you.

Other tips and tidbits: Murphy's estimated birthday is 6/24/18

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description: If interested in adopting a pet from our shelter you will need to fill out a request to adopt. There will be a overnight wait to get this approved. If approved, there is a $20 adoption fee for cats, and kittens. Adult dogs adoption fee is $75.00. Adoption fees for adult dogs at the shelter more than 2 weeks reduces to $25. Adoption fee for puppies or purebred dogs (no papers) is $100.  If not spayed or neutered, a deposit is required. The deposit is $130 for dogs and $55 for cats. Your deposit is returned after the animal is spayed/neutered. All animals adopted from the shelter MUST be spayed/neutered. Dogs arriving at the shelter receive DA2PP and Bordetella. Cats receive a vaccine for Rhinotracheitis-Calici-Panleukopenia-Chlamydia Psittaci. The animals at our shelter have been picked up stray. Please remember this when requesting additional information about the animals. Questions can be emailed to emporiakansasanimalshelter@gmail.com

animal.description:
Carolina Boxer Rescue is a volunteer run, 501(c)3 non-profit organization. Our mission: To balance the health, safety, and welfare needs of Boxers in the Carolinas (and parts of Virginia and Georgia) by providing a loving and safe environment for stray, abused, impounded and owner surrendered dogs by placing them in foster homes and ultimately - forever homes.

________________________________________________________________________________________

Dog's Name: Karma

Dog's Approximate Age: 6 years

Gender: Female

Dog's Size: Medium (50lbs to 70lbs. as adult and healthy weight)

Dog's Weight: Don't know yet

Good with small dogs?: Yes

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Yes

Good with kids?: Yes, all ages

Any medical issues?: Karma is currently being monitored by the vet for joint discomfort.

Crate trained?: Yes

House trained?: Yes

Heartworms?: No

7/19/20: Hello everyone!! My name is Karma, and I'm a big snuggle bug! I have fallen in love with the couch at my new foster mom's house. She puts blankets down for me to curl up on, and I love it! I also love to lay in the sun during the early mornings before it gets too hot outside. The family has another Boxer who is all full of energy and he keeps bringing me toys to play with, but I'd rather snuggle and give kisses. I keep eyeballing the beds, but right now they are too high for me to climb up on, so my foster mom said she's got a plan that will allow me to get up on the beds. I can't wait to cuddle at night with the little people in the house. Right now one of the little people sleeps in the living room with me so I'm not alone at night. It's kinda nice having her there with me to keep me company. I've been here since Sunday and have made sure to not have any accidents or chew anything that I'm not supposed to :-) My foster mom says I'm SUCH a good girl because she doesn't have to crate me when she goes to the store. One of the things that I really love is to watch the lizard and the bunnies that are here. One bunny even kisses me on the nose. They are so fun to watch! My foster family has a cat too, but she's not very exciting. She just stares at me, but thankfully she doesn't seem to mind that I'm here for a bit. I have a really awesome sponsor named Erin Simpson that sent me goodies in the mail and another person who made me a really awesome blanket that's all mine! I'm super spoiled and getting lots of love and affection. So far I've made two trips to the vet for check ups and I have to say, car rides are pretty fun! My foster mom gets me french fries after my vet appointments which are super yummy! I can't wait to have a place to call my home and a family to claim as mine :-) I'm SO thankful Carolina Boxer Rescue came and rescued me because now I feel like a princess that's loved :-)

_____________________________________________________________________________

Come visit carolinaboxerrescue.org to learn more about me and see more pictures. Learn about our adoption process too!

_____________________________________________________________________________

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Sweet Pea! I am very pretty and have cool brindle spots and some freckles. My eyes are full of expression and beautiful. I am a very compassionate dog and will make someone a great companion. I can tell when you need a hug or cuddles and give them freely. I can jump really high (I could probably clear a four foot fence, but have never tried), when I get excited. I am very curious and love to explore both inside and outside.

I spent my first three years of life living outdoors in a kennel. I was surrendered to Save-a-Bull and adjusted to inside life pretty quickly. I was adopted and lived with my new family for about six months, but my prey drive got the best of me and I had a run in with the family cat. Sadly, I was surrendered to Save-a-Bull again, and I am being fostered by the same family and I am loving hanging out with them.

I am kennel and potty trained! I have been sleeping in my foster's bed and I love to cuddle. Right now I am relaxing and adjusting to my current situation. I have mastered sit, shake, touch, wait and lift (to get the leash out from behind my front paws when we walk). I love treats - the stinkier, the better! I would love to take a training class with you, so we can bond and I can show you how smart I am. I would also love to do some agility training, as I am very athletic.

I have lived with a toddler and we did well together. I also met a baby and was not impressed, but I left her alone. I think I would enjoy living with older children who can help train me and give me good cuddles. I like to give hugs and might be too much for smaller children to handle. I would not do well living with cats or smaller animals - I have a big prey drive and it gets me into trouble. I have lived with other big dogs, both of them were male. I adapt to other dogs very well - I adapt to their play style and will stop when they indicate that they are done. I will try to encourage play-by-play bowing and giving playful barks. If that does not work, I back off. I read other dogs extremely well. I love to go for walks and I love to wrestle with other dogs.

I need a family that will give me some time to adjust to a new home. I need to be reassured that everything is okay and that you love me and I can trust you. Once we have bonded, I will be your best friend for life. I adjust to my situation very well and fast. If you want to go biking, I will be ready and willing to walk all day. If you want to spend the day watching TV and chilling, I will be your cuddle buddy and enjoy spending time just hanging out with you. I just want to be included in your activities and adventures.

My dream day would consist of hanging out with my family and being rewarded with good treats and great company. Could that be you?

Date into Rescue: 01/18/20
Reason for being in rescue: puppy mill bust
Foster location: Foster Home in Union, SC
Special Needs? Betty has nursed her last litter of puppies. She has been spayed, had a dental polishing on 5/29/20, and is ready for her forever home.
Weight: 8.60 lb
Height: 6 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? We are seeking a home with an experienced dog owner and someone who is home more than they're away. Betty needs an experienced chihuahua owner. She is not for a first time dog owner. She is not for a home with children. She needs someone that understands her breed and has the patience to help her continue to learn what it means to be a pet. She is much better with male dogs - of any size. She marks around other little girls.

What is my personality like? Betty came to CPR from a puppy mill bust in Laurens, SC. She was pregnant and gave birth to one baby girl the second day she was here, but unfortunately her pup was born with a birth defect and did not make it. Betty stepped up to nurse another litter of orphaned pups. It is clear that all Betty has known is being a mom.

Betty is very timid at first, but once you gain her trust she is all yours. Most of her life has been spent as a breeding dog, which means limited socialization and human interaction. Betty is a classic chihuahua - feisty, sometimes moody, but incredibly loyal. She likes things on her terms. Betty enjoys sitting in a lap but would be equally happy sitting beside you on the couch. She is content to sleep in a dog bed at night. She has impeccable house manners in her foster home.

Betty is a wonderful dog. She would be great for quiet retirees looking for a dog to share their heart with. She does not require a ton of exercise and really just wants a quiet life.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Timid and shy at first.

Other tips and tidbits: Betty's estimated birthday is 1/15/2012.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

animal.description:
Meet Bingo!  He is guessed to be about 3-4 years old and weighs 55 lbs.  He came from a farm in Indiana where he was free roaming and the neighbors threatened to shoot him if found on their property, so the owner decided to surrender him for their safety.  

Bingo can be slow to warm up to new people, so he is looking for a patient adopter who will understand he needs a slow approach to build his trust. Once he trusts you he is just a happy goofy boy.  His favorite things are treats and squirrel watching in the yard.  He has had no accidents in the house and usually only barks if he sees someone walking by the house.  He gets along with the other dogs in his foster home (between 3-20 lbs), except for one little young male chihuahua that has it out for him.  We would describe Bingo's interactions with other dogs as coexisting- basically not seeking out attention or engaging in play, but fine being around the other dogs.  If his new home had dog siblings we think he would do best with dogs that would respect his space and be happy to coexist with him.  

Bingo is currently living with a (very dog savvy) 2 year old and he has done very good with him, however Bingo is VERY clumsy and doesn't really know his size and has knocked over the toddler numerus times.  For that reason we think an all adult home or home with older, dog savvy children would be best.  

He can be nervous in busy environments, so ideally we are looking for a quiet setting for this boy- away from a lot of traffic (both pedestrian and vehicle) and a quieter home without a lot of new visitors.  He is still learning how to walk nicely on a leash and has made so much progress from when we first got him. He can be a bit erratic, so you have to have a good grip on the leash and be prepared for when he tries to change directions quickly.  We think with increased expsure to leash walking he will be a pro in no time!

He is at risk for jumping fences, so we will be carefully screening applicants to ensure that measures would be in place to keep him safe and secure if a fence is to be used as the primary method of containment outside.  

Bingo has a cataract in his right eye and also glaucoma in that eye.  He is currently getting eye drops and ointment twice a day in hopes to reduce and maintain the pressure, but if medications do not work he may need that eye removed down the road.  He also was treated for Lymes disease and no further treatment is necessary at this point.  

Bingo's adoption donation of $250 helps cover the cost of his medical care.  

Application, reference checks, and home visit required. Adopters must live 1.5 hours driving distance from Romeoville, IL. For more information on adopting, please email us at info@perfectpooches.org.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete an adoption application, which can be found on our website at www.perfectpooches.org under the Adoption Process tab.  All dogs are spayed/neutered, current on vaccines, heartworm tested (age appropriate), fecal tested and/or dewormed, and microchipped.

Date into Rescue: 09/21/2018 original intake, adopted but returned June 2020
Reason for being in rescue: In 2018, Marty Bear Doodle was left tied to the outside of an animal shelter in GA by his owners. CPR pulled him from the shelter. We placed him but he returned to us a year later when his two-person, socially active home realized he would be happier in a quieter environment.
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Horrible ears - we've resolved the infection for now but he will need to be watched for life on his ears. He is on a bi-weekly ointment for his ears. Marty Bear Doodle also has extensive discospondylitis and lumbosacral disease. He sometimes need to have a medication called methacarbonal when his back goes out. Finally, Marty is HIGHLY flea allergic. A single flea will cause a major skin issue. He must be on regular monthly preventative.

Weight: 14.2 lb
Height: 13 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes - leashes scare Marty "Care Bear" (our nickname for him is Care Bear. He would be happier with his own yard to romp and play in.

What kind of home would be best for me? Care Bear requires a special quiet home that would be willing to work around his quirks and help him become the dog he has the potential to be. He needs an experienced dog owner with the patience to earn his trust. A calm home with little distractions.

What is my personality like? Care Bear needs a quiet home with very few changes or visitors. He is smart and sensitive to his environment. He will need patience communicating his needs to you. He was potty trained in his home and could go outside in a fenced yard with no leash. He will walk on a leash, but they scare him and he prefers to be home instead. He will bark at you if you do not give him time to adjust to the change (going outside/inside).

Bear could be an only dog with a patient human or he could have calm, stable doggie companions. The big thing for Bear is no change. Bear likes treats and responds well to treats before a change; transitions/change is difficult for him. The types of changes that are seem to be focused on someone coming in or out of the house. In his current foster home, change is constant and he's getting used to it. With the right understanding owner, he would be great. We know this boy deserves to have a special person to help him and we hope we can find the right person and home for him!

Bear is very food oriented and this is the way to his heart. So far he has gotten along with other dogs he has met but in his home he was not happy with other dogs - probably because they came in or out. When he is scared of another dog, he barks at them like he's never been around other dogs before.

Bear is a special boy whose past is a mystery and whose future needs patience and a firm and experienced handler. In the right home, Bear will be an amazing companion and best friend.

Important Note: Bear sheds slightly - less when he is kept short. He is not hypoallergenic. We think he is a mix of long haired jack russell and poodle.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Cautious and nervous at first. Come with treats. That makes all the difference.

Other tips and tidbits: Marty Bear's estimated birthday is 9/21/2011

House trained? Bear is crate trained and responding well to outside schedule. Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
Traveler is a 9 year old Beagle that came from South Carolina found as a stray. We believe he is a discarded hunting dog, Traveler struggled with socializing with people, and has come a long way while in foster care.

Great Points:
Traveler is very shy but just as sweet as can be! He is great with kids, other dogs, and didn't really react to cats the few times he's been around them. He has great leash manners, crate trained, and an all-around good boy!

Best Home:
Traveler's perfect family would have a quieter home, ideally with a retired person or couple. Traveler is loving retirement life and would enjoy sharing his golden years with his people. He loves long walks, naps, breakfast time, and following his people around. He does need to be crated when home alone, but he's very happy with it and will often nap in there anyway. New people and unfamiliar sounds make him nervous, so he would love someone with a little patience to help him come out of his shell and show him all the love. He would need a fenced in yard, as he does have a tendency to exit seek when he gets nervous. He would do great with another dog pal, but he would be fine without one as well.

Submit your applications at: https://oneloveanimalrescue.com/pre-adoption-application/

animal.description:
Age: 8 years
Weight: 7.5 lbs.
Adoption Fee: $250
Fostered in Baton Rouge, Louisiana

7/31/20 - Kiki went to the dogtor yesterday to get all updated.  Her mouth was so bad, she lost 18 teeth.  Glad those bad things are gone.  She has 2 teeth left and won't mind eating soft food AT ALL since she is such a food hog.  This is why it is so important to get regular dentals performed, on smaller dogs especially. The results can be a toothless wonder at a young age.  Oh well, what's done is done and Kiki is still happy and cute.

7/23/20 - To quote Louis Sabin, “No matter how little money and how few possessions you own, having a dog makes you rich”.  So, Kiki wants to know just how rich do you want to be?

Kiki isn’t one of those totally clingy yorkies that is all about herself.  I know, shocking, right?  Don’t get us wrong, she is a female and does demand a certain amount of love and affection, but she doesn’t have to be the one on your lap all the time.  We are hoping this will change once she gets into a home with just 1 or 2 other dogs.  She is co-existing fine with the other dogs in the house but does not play with them or toys quite yet for that matter.  She is a very hearty eater and tries to convince the humans to share their food with her.  Not going to happen little girl!

She is very social and never meets a stranger.  Kiki is a talker (barker), so an apartment would not be the best digs for her.  She also needs a secure fenced in yard and humans that are very careful with open doors since she is very interested in “the other side”.  Maybe this is how she became stray.  We think she obviously had a nice family that loved her at some point in her life, but she was picked up stray and brought to the local shelter.  The shelter and Yorkie Haven Rescue reached out far and wide to locate an owner, but perhaps it was just meant for Kiki to move on.

At first, Kiki felt crowded and didn’t want to sleep in the human bed, but she is now coming around and seems to like to share the human pillow.  This will be another plus for her with less dogs.  She will definitely have some accidents as it will take time for her to get adjusted, but she will go outside when brought, just needs to be brought often.  Even though Kiki isn’t clingy, she does like to give kisses.  And foster mom loves to get them.
Her legs are a little longer, so jumping up and down on the sofa isn’t a challenge for her, but to get in the bed, she will either need steps, or to be put up and down.

So, going back to that “having a dog makes you rich” quote.  What’s say you and I buy a lottery ticket….. TOGETHER!

animal.description:
Breed: Pit Bull Terrier
Sex: Neutered Male
DOB: ~01/29/2017
Weight: 59 lbs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Fun. Silly, Excitable, Playful, Snuggly 
History: Stray
Good With: Some Dogs
Fence Requirements: Fence required
Ideal Home: Experienced home without children or cats. Low-traffic home. No apartments!
Special Info:

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

ATTENTION: PLEASE READ THROUGH TO SEE WHETHER YOU MEET OUR ADOPTION CRITERIA BEFORE RESPONDING. IF YOU MEET OUR CRITERIA FOR ADOPTION OF THIS DOG, PLEASE FOLLOW THE LINK TOWARD THE BOTTOM OF THE PROFILE TO COMPLETE OUR ONLINE APPLICATION. THANK YOU!

Meet Roscoe!

Roscoe is a super sweet, loyal affectionate young staffie who loves to play with other dogs. We believe Roscoe is 1.5 years old. He is very small for the breed at about 40lbs. 

Roscoe was rescued by a Good Samaritan after his first owner moved from his apartment and left Roscoe behind. The first owner had not neutered or vaccined him and worst of all, he hadn’t trained him either. Poor boy!

Since being in the care of people who care, Roscoe has been neutered and vaccined and has come a long way in his training. He is a young, playful and athletic dog and needs continued training in his new home. He wants to be by ‘his’ person’s side and really wants to please his person. 

Our primary criteria for placement of Roscoe is a home with a securely fenced backyard, people who aren’t gone from the home excessive hours. He would be best as an only dog or with a dog companion who is his size or bigger and very calm. 

Adoption Process: We are not first come first served. Indigo Rescue focuses on finding good matches between dogs and families to ensure life long adoptions. We deliver all dogs to their new homes. All of our dogs are in foster homes. If you’re interested in meeting one of our dogs, please complete our adoption application using the following link, The link is not live, so you will need to copy and paste it into your browser:  https://storage.googleapis.com/gator-users/user680788/documents/d1742bff02e44c2ea25649cb45df5103/Pet%20Application%20Form%20December%202020.pdf
If the dog you're interested in seems compatible with your lifestyle we'll set up a time for you to meet the dog privately.
PLEASE NOTE: Indigo Rescue only adopts to homes within 30 miles of Beaverton because our volunteers deliver all of our dogs to their adoptive homes. We work very hard to create a family of our Indigo Rescue adopters because we want to be close enough to help in case there are any problems. We want everyone to be happy and successful!

**ALL of our dogs, puppies, cats, kittens and rabbits come vaccined to their age, spayed/neutered and microchipped.

Thank you for your interest in adopting and saving a life.

animal.description:
Also in need of a foster home ~ 
NMDOG KENZIE is available for adoption to a very special human! 


KENZIE is a Belgian Malinois / Border Collie cross, per her DNA test results. She is NOT going to be a typical family pet & will not be placed as one. In KENZIES best interest & in our best efforts to set KENZIE & her people up for success...we are ONLY seeking those w breed/handling & training experience with working dogs. We employ & condone only positive, fear/force free training methods. We also expect KENZIE to live inside of the home with her human, as a treasured companion. Working can either be done professionally or as a hobby...as long as KENZIE is treated with respect, has structure & a "job" meeting all of her needs, she will be an absolute treasure of a dog! If you are not interested in SAR work, extreme agility/flyball or luring, LE/Cadaver work, etc...you are not the right human for KENZIE. If you have small children &/or other animals in your home or in your immediate circle.....you are not the right human for KENZIE. If you are still reading....please, allow us to tell you more! 

KENZIE was first discovered as a 3 mo old pup "living" at the end of her chain on a NM Indian Reservation. She was suffering terribly with a severe case of demodectic mange & starvation. Because of "sovereign protections" there was nothing that could legally be done to remove her from the situation. Over time (6 mos to be exact) & with the dedication of a handful of motivated people....KENZIE was finally legally signed over to NMDOG. Her condition was now much, much worse & mentally....the neglect & cruelty had began taking its toll. This was the only "life" KENZIE had ever known. Initially, KENZIE was extremely painful to the touch, her skin was completely infected, covered in oozy rotten scabs & open sores. Even the bottom of her feet were raw with mange. KENZIE weighed only 32# at 9mos old when she first entered the NMDOG program & never in her life, had she experienced a comforting touch, a kind word, a soft clean bed or a warm meal. Over the first few months, KENZIE learned that human touch was good & it provided comfort, not pain. She learned not to bite the hand that feeds her & over time...she stopped guarding her meals & possessions. Now KENZIE happily obliges in a game of "drop it - leave it".  KENZIE has incredible drive & is constantly working on impulse control - but being in a kennel situation as KENZIE currently is, with limited volunteer time, puts limits on KENZIES progress. She needs her very own super dedicated & FUN human in order to truly thrive!! KENZIE is wicked smart as you can imagine - (see Malinios/Border Collie X), smarter than most humans we know :) Shes going to require someone that can always stay a step ahead of KENZIE & quide her in the right direction. We believe KENZIE deserves to fulfill her absolute potential in life & we are looking for the special human to help her do just that! If you are interested in KENZIE, please reach out to us right away!! 

As an all volunteer, foster based, 501(c)3 non profit rescue, NMDOG is always in need of new, approved foster & adoptive homes in order to continue our Mission: to serve & protect New Mexico's Forgotten Dogs!! 

If you see a dog you are interested in that says "in need of a foster home", we are currently seeking a temporary foster home for that dog in order to provide them with the cozy & loving experience of a home environment while we work hard to find their forever family. This also frees up space & funds, which enables us to save another life. There is never a cost to foster for NMDOG & you will have the dedicated support of the NMDOG TEAM every step of the way. We take the time to really get to know the needs & personalities of our kids & we go the extra mile to ensure we make the best possible match...setting our dogs & their humans up for success! To learn more about the NMDOG foster program & to submit the foster application, please visit this link on our website - www.nmdog.org/foster

Our adoption fee is $250 which includes; a 7 week NMDOG obedience/bonding class with their new family (classes are located in Abq & are also offered to our foster guardians), a complimentary vet wellness check & our dogs come with all of the supplies they need to get started on a trial adoption in their new home. All adopted dogs also receive free or discounted goodies & services from many of our awesome community partners!! Grooming, food, training, boarding, pet sitting & more. To learn more about the NMDOG adoption process & to submit the adoption application, please visit this link on our website - www.nmdog.org/adopt 

NMDOG doesn't cut any corners when it comes to the care & placement of our dogs. When a dog enters the NMDOG program, they are guaranteed to receive the very best of care. All of our available dogs have received a full medical & behavioral clearance prior to placement. They are (at the very minimum) spayed or neutered, UTD on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped, dewormed, Heartworm tested & currently on HW/flea & tick preventative. Due to the nature of our work, many of the dogs we rescue need much more extensive care before they are cleared for adoption. At NMDOG, we stand by our dogs for life & we make a promise to always be there for them (& their people) should they ever need us. . 

Please contact us directly via the links provided above or email info@nmdog.org with your interest in becoming a treasured NMDOG Foster Guardian or FoReVeR Guardian Angel to one of our amazing dogs in need!
We look forward to hearing from you & answering any questions you may have. WooF!!

animal.description:
Wylie

Located in western Nebraska 
3 years old
"Purebred" German Shepherd (I'm writing what we were told, we don't DNA our dogs, we think he may be a mix)
Good with some dogs as long as it's not a pack situation
Not sure on cats 
Good with older children 
Great with guinea pigs (or he was when he was surrendered, now we are told he has a high prey drive, not sure about this)
Insanely sweet
Has had a lot of chaos in his life and needs a calm, breed educated and patient home
House trained
Needs mental stimulation 
Needs physical stimulation 
We were told he was crate trained but so far not the case, so this will need work
Fully vetted 
65lbs

PLEASE READ THE DESCRIPTION BELOW BEFORE ASKING QUESTIONS AS THEY MAY ALREADY BE ANSWERED

This handsome boy is Wylie. Wylie's story is an epically sad and discouraging one.

Wylie has been in his current adoptive home since November 17th. This is a German Shepherd knowledgeable home however they do have multiple dogs and a couple are older. When they took him they knew he was very protective of his home, needed mental and physical exercise and had some legit separation anxiety. We got rave reviews until the end of March. After this home adopted another HPPAW German Shepherd we were informed of issues and told they had been happening for months, this was coming Grady to what we had heard but we started to make arrangements to take him back. In April we were told that the issues had subsided and they just couldn't get rid of him they loved him too much. We were so happy and relieved for Wylie that he would get to stay with the people he had grown to know and love. However then a week ago we were again contacted and told he needed to move, this time immediately. We explained our confusion and asked for answers, what we got wasn't answers. It is what it is. At this point Wylie needs to move to ensure his safety. The adopters told us that against the adoption contract they tried to surrender the dog to the shelter who refused, knowing better. They also told us they considered trying to rehome him themselves but then didn't feel that was a good idea. So now here we are, with poor Wylie being again rehomed and losing the people he trusts again. 

This sweet boy needs a patient home with no dogs or just a couple dogs. We cannot express the importance enough of a patient and understanding home. This home may have started out like that but apparently for at least one adult in the home that changed drastically. Wylie has anxiety and needs help with that, it's been apparently made worse not better since March. At this point we believe that a lot of the current issues may be situational but we cannot say that for sure. 

We find this very discouraging for Wylie. He doesn't deserve everything that's happened to him. He needs love, patience and stability. 

Original Story

We were alerted to Wylie by a rescue friend when he was at risk for being shot for nipping a kid. Now before everyone dooms him lets get a better understanding of the situation he was in that this supposed "nip" happened. The home had SEVERAL foster children, which is an amazing thing to do, however with having over 5 rotating foster kids of various ages with various issues and no one having seen said incident it's not something we are willing to doom him for. A woman who works with this family in a professional manner reached out to some eastern NE rescues and asked for help because they did not believe this dog deserved that end. We agree, NO DOG deserves that end. Anyway, we were contacted and had a foster who had offered for another German Shepherd who, who was adopted, that immediately agreed to take him. He is very sweet and friendly and up until the point he transported to us his BFF was a guinea pig! He went to a fosters home and she immediately fell in love with him and decided she wanted to keep him, so Wylie had never been listed. She made us aware that he had some serious separation anxiety but that she wanted to work through it. We had had multiple conversations with the foster in regards to his issues and all ended the same way, we other her wanting to work through it. We supplied an escape proof crate, and advice and thought that the conditioning was going well however we were then alerted that was NOT the case and that this sweet boy needed to move immediately. His foster has worked with HPPAW for years and while this is very upsetting and emotional we ALWAYS understand every dog isn't a fit for every home. We were as heartbroken about it as she was on multiple levels, but mostly for sweet Wylie as he is again losing the home and family he knows.

 

This lug needs a breed experienced (or similar breed experienced home) and patient home to work with him on his separation anxiety. He also is a bit over protective of his yard and family, again, breed experience would help here as this is epically common with German Shepherds and we have zero desire to punish him for doing what he was bred to do, but he needs an equipped home. 

 $200.00 Adoption Fee 
(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.) 

If you feel your home and family would be a good fit for sweet Wylie please contact us!

animal.description:
Blue is back up for adoption.   Blue CANNOT live in a townhouse, condo, apartment or house in the suburbs.  He MUST live in a home in the MOUNTAINS or in the MIDDLE OF NO WHERE.  After much evaluation and consultations we have decided Blue will do very well in a very specific home environment. He is a great dog, smart, sweet, and very trainable. But he needs a quiet home with a solid routine and experienced dog owners. He is looking for a home up in the mountains or on a farm where he can get lots of exercise but not run into people or dogs he doesn't know. He gets along great with the dogs in his home but over reacts when meeting people and dogs on walks. He is very protective of his home and car. He is a great guard dog. We are looking for a house with no weekly gardener, housekeepers or garbage men who come too close to the house. He finds them very threatening. Where he is now, the garbage cans are picked up at the end of the driveway where he can't see them and all is peace on garbage day.

We are looking for a peaceful home and a mom or dad with a big heart to take in this very special boy. He would do well in a multi dog household but no kids or cats. While he would love your kids he would not like their visiting friends.  Blue is only 2 years old and is currently in Romoland, California.

If you would like to make this special boy part of your family, please fill out an application.  His adoption fee is $550.

. 18 months old. 75#. 

After 10 months in boarding because my owner fell ill, I am having a great time playing with other dogs in my foster home!  I am very leery and skittish initially, but as soon as I realize you’re a good person, I warm up and give you more love than you can imagine! It only took me one day to learn to trust and love my foster mom...I have a lot of love to give! I haven’t had much experience on a leash, but amazingly I walk quite well on one.
I ride great in the car.  I enjoy my crate, it gives me security. I have plenty of energy and would like an active household that would take me out walking, hiking, or even running. I love to play and will fetch a ball and would get along just fine
with another dog playmate.  I have not met a cat, but due to my breed mix, I would most likely chase one.
Kids would be just fine, but probably old enough to understand my playful nature that might knock over the younger ones.
I am a gorgeous auburn color underneath my brindle stripes.  You will be having to stop to let other people admire me when you take me out in public. A fenced yard is highly highly recommended due to my skittish nature and hound mixture.   My house manners are very good, too! 
Trust me, if you adopt me, you will wonder how you ever lived without me at your side!

animal.description:
Rosie is a young female pit mix who is looking for her forever home! She will require a family that is familiar with stronger breeds and rescue dogs. She is super sweet with people but has some reactivity with other dogs and can be fearful in new situations/of loud noises. With consistent and structured training we believe she can get better at being more calm and social around other dogs her size.

Rosie would thrive in a calm home that can provide her structure and where she can decompress. She loves getting attention and pets from her people and is very treat motivated. 

Rosie is smart and willing to learn if you have some yummy treats! Rosie is crate and potty trained, sleeps well in her crate throughout the night. She LOVES getting belly rubs and shoulder massages from her family, and enjoys the company of people. 

Due to her fears and reactivity, she requires a free standing home outside of the city with a fenced in yard. She needs to be the only dog in the home with no cats and kids over the age of 12 that are respectful. 

Rosie is UTD on shots, microchipped and spayed. Her adoption fee is $350.

We do not know what she thinks about cats. Mona had tested positive for Ehrlichia, a common tick borne disease similar to Lyme's.  She has completed her course of treatment and has been feeling fine.  Mona is about 5 years old and 40 pounds.  Please help Mona find the loving home she deserves.

We do NOT ship our animals. All adoptive families must travel to us to meet their adoptive dog/cat. Applicants must live within a 2 hour radius from Sparta/Andover (07871/07821).

Please understand that we are an animal shelter and thus unable to say whether the dogs are housebroken as they are not in homes.

If you are interested in adopting, we encourage you to please submit an application on our website today so that we can try and process and pre-approve any potential adopters prior to our next adoption event.

animal.description:
Fans of our rescue may remember the adorable Atreyu who is now known as Cooper!! He was adopted last spring by an amazing family who adores him, but we have been working together extensively and have made the very difficult decision to try to find him another home! 

Cooper is about 2 years old, and is constantly on the go! Nothing pleases him more than a game of fetch with a ball or frisbee. He is a fantastic soccer goalie, and prefers toys over treats! Cooper loves adventuring through trails, running alongside a bike, checking out the ocean and riding in the truck. He absolutely loves car rides and does great on road trips! 

Cooper is intelligent and inquisitive and picks up commands easily....he also just completed a 2 week board and train, and have mastered his training skills even more! (plus his adoption includes a consultation with these trainers as a follow up to help him succeed in his new home!) While eager to play, Cooper also loves to cuddle at the end of a long day. He enjoys sleeping under a blanket or next to a human and is the sweetest boy! He loves to greet visitors with tail wags and kisses. Cooper is full of love and up for anything. He is a wonderful dog with a fun, quirky personality! 

The reason Cooper is in need of a new family is because he has become reactive towards young children, and other pups. For this reason, we feel he would THRIVE in a home without kids where he can be the one and only! He is a really amazing guy, who just needs a more quiet home where he can really succeed....and we just know the right family is out there for him!

Cooper is up to date on vaccines, and is neutered, and on preventatives, and as mentioned above would come with some consultations with our trainers to make sure he has everything he needs to succeed! When in an environment without other pups he is an absolute STAR, so he just needs the right family to see him and snatch him up! 

Interested in this handsome boy?? Get your application in here: 

www.harleyshavendogrescue.com/adopt

Don't miss your chance on this sweet boy!

***PLEASE NOTE:  Our adoption radius is 60 minutes from Perkasie, PA.  We do not ship/transport our dogs***

animal.description: This sad gal came to us with a mammary tumor the size of a grapefruit along with a large hernia.  Said to be 13 she can be cranky and will nip unless treated gently and carefully. But when she knows her human she is a love!   The cute factor is huge as well as her incredible spirit.  Tumor hanging down, as huge as it is, she was full of beans and behaved as if a regular old dog with out a care in the world.  I see dachshund tenacity and personality.  Post surgery was tough and touch and go with bruising and a lot of pain.  But she is a strong dog and came through and is now completely healed.  We did not biopsy so with Helen you think pawsitively and send great energies her way because in our book she has beat the odds thanks to a great surgeon and her healing abilities.  She has also made huge strides in her behavior and has allowed volunteers to get close and even pick her up now.  She is a very sweet little lady

animal.description:
Oz is a handsome 3-year old male Labrador Retriever/Pit Bull Terrier/Boxer mix who was surrendered by his owner on June 19, 2020 along with a few of his best friends who shared his previous home including Pirate and Wizard (Labrador Retriever/Pit Bull Terrier/Boxer mixes) and Shaggy (Beagle).

Oz has a white short smooth coat, a long tail, and a noble-looking face with dark brown eyes, a black/pink nose, and large white floppy ears which are sprinkled with black spots.

Oz was understandably 'out of his element' when he first arrived at our shelter and being in an unfamiliar place with folks that he didn't yet know or trust :)  Oz was a very frightened boy and wasn't ready to venture from the security of his kennel for outdoor photos when we took preliminary pictures on June 20th on his kuranda bed with a promise to take more flattering ones at a later date.

We were delighted to have an opportunity to take updated photos of Oz during an after-hours dog walk at the shelter on July 16, 2020.   Oz was accompanied by one of his favorite volunteers (Fredley Tynan) who helped him with his photo session.  Oz was also encouraged and had his self-confidence bolstered when he saw other members of his fan club (and two of his former housemates)  :)  Oz 'perked up' when he saw John and Lynncoln Tynan with Oz' friends Pirate and Wizard cheering him on and helping him with his 'Westminster Show Dog' Poses :)

Oz is still cautious around folks that he doesn't know well, but he is making progress with his trust issues.  Our kennel techs (and also the Tynan family) would be happy to introduce you to Oz if you are interested in giving him a fabulous home.

Oz weighs 55 lbs. He will be neutered before being adopted by his new family.

Oz was neutered on July 29, 2020 and was also given rabies vaccine.

animal.description:
Biscotti is a 5 year old male Pomeranian rescued from a puppy mill.
He spent the first 2 years of his life in the house being a pet, learning commands. Once the babies came he was moved to the kennel with larger dogs where his leg muscle was ripped and lost one of his toes. 
We then were called to rescue him.
He was not used to living in the house with a family. He will not do well with children and would do best in a quiet home. It makes him nervous to sit in a lap but he wants to be near his people next to them or at their feet. When he came to us he had been shaved which is not good for Pomeranians. Our groomer has performed magic and he is beautiful. He also did very well at the groomer.

Biscotti wants to love and trust but it will take time and patience.

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA. 

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

animal.description: Spent time with Red Robin today and he is alert and doesnt miss a thing.  He gives full warning of how far to push things but did take chicken from our hands and very gently at that.   He is very vocal, talks and changes what he says depending on what he thinks is going to happen.  Marvin our pig is helping with him and being very respectful. Red may have rear osteo pain affecting his temperament so started him on pain meds which they were administering at LA AS. .  Meade Canine works well for dogs like Red Robin who really don't have many options and are often first to be euthanized.  And watching dogs react to dogs like Red Robin is interesting, adding to dogs complexities.  He is now coming in and staying in the house and hang out where dogs congregate but basically he resembles a feral dog and looks a lot like a coyote.  If you have a ranch or barn where he can wander about undisturbed or you want to take the time with him to make him trust and respect you that would be great but for now I think Red is here to stay!  People think he is a coyote when they see him and tend to avoid him but we are quite happy he is here.  He follows us everywhere come dinner time.  Red Robin is making strides quickly.
